y || 10 || Carlaw Park # 1, 2pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 20 Oct || City || 11 || Devonport || 3 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 20 Oct || Richmond || 11 || Newton || 5 || Carlaw Park # 2, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 20 Oct || Ponsonby || 25 || Point Chevalier || 13 || Carlaw Park # 2, 4pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 20 Oct || Marist || 11 || Ellerslie || 8 || Carlaw Park # 1, 4pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 27 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title = Labour Day Competition/Marist Team Successful\n| page =13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20089\n| date = 1928-10-29\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281029.2.137.11\n| accessdate = 2019-10-05}}</ref>\n|| Richmond|| 11 || Ponsonby || 5 || Carlaw Park # 1, 2pm||2,500\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 27 Oct || Marist|| 17 || City || 12 || Carlaw Park # 2, 2pm \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Final\n| 27 Oct || Marist|| 12 || Richmond|| 5 || Carlaw Park # 1, 4pm \n|-\n|}\n\n==Other Club Matches and Lower Grades==\n===Lower Grade Clubs===\n<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Competitions\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIX| issue=256\n| date = 1928-10-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19281029.2.133.8\n| accessdate = 2019-10-05}}</ref>\nGrades were made of the following teams with the winning teams in bold:\n*'''Second Grade''': Akarana, Devonport, Mangere, Newton, Northcote, Ponsonby, Remuera, Richmond (Won by Devonport who were 6 pts clear of Remuera, Ponsonby and Newton), (Newton won the knockout competition)\n*'''Third Grade Open''': Athletic, Devonport A, Devonport B, Ellerslie, Glen Eden, Kingsland, Mount Albert, New Lynn, Northcote, Otahuhu, Parnell, Ponsonby, Richmond (Won by Richmond, 2 pts clear or Mount Albert) (Richmond won the knockout competition)\n*'''Third Grade Intermediate''': City, Devonport, New Lynn, Newton, Newmarket, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby, Remuera, Richmond (Won by Richmond, 8pts clear of Ponsonby), (Richmond won the knockout competition)\n*'''Fourth Grade''': Akarana, City, Devonport, Ellerslie, Northcote, Otahuhu, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby, Remuera, Richmond (Won by Richmond, 2 pts clear of Remuera, Richmond also won the knockout compeitition)\n*'''Fifth Grade''': Akarana, Athletic, Brown Brothers and Geddes, Devonport, Mount Albert, Richmond (Won by Akarana, 6pts clear of Devonport), (Devonport beat Richmond 15-7 in the knockout final)\n*'''Sixth Grade A''': Akarana, Devonport, Ellerslie, Kingsland, Marist, Newmarket, Northcote, Otahuhu, Richmond, Point Chevalier (Won by Point Chevalier, 6pts clear of Richmond, Richmond won the knockout competition.\n*'''Sixth Grade B''': Akarana, City, Devonport, Marist, Newmarket, Newton, Point Chevalier, Richmond (Won by Point Chevalier, 5 pts clear of Marist, Marist won the knockout competition.\n*'''Primary Schools''': Ellerslie, Mangere, Mount Albert, Newmarket, Newton, Onehunga, Onehunga Convent, Otahuhu, Otahuhu B, Papatoetoe, Richmond (Otahuhu won the final of the school knockout competition after defeating Onehunga Convent 13 to 3).\nRichmond were awarded the Davis\u2019 Points Shield for most junior grade wins. They gained 75 points, with Devonport finishing second.\n\n===Exhibition Matches===\n[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] travelled north to play [[Hikurangi]] in the first rugby league match in the area. The local rugby team had become dissatisfied with their treatment by the rugby union and had switched to the league code. [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] won the match in poor weather by 5 points to 0.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | List of Exhibition Matches\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 7 July <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Games in the Province/Hikurangi\n| page =12\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]\n| date = 1928-07-09\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280709.2.134.8\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi|| 0 || Richmond || 5 || Hikurangi \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 8 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Results\n| page =14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIX| issue=196\n| date = 1928-08-20\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280820.2.132.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi|| 13 || Richmond B || 17 || Hikurangi \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 1 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ponsonby V Hikurangi\n| page = 13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20041\n| date = 1928-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280903.2.135.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi||10 || Ponsonby ||22 ||Hikurangi \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 1 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ponsonby in the North/Games at Hikurangi\n| page =12\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIX| issue=208\n| date = 1928-09-03\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280903.2.153.6\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi Juniors||5 || Ponsonby Juniors ||11 ||Hikurangi \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 1 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ponsonby V Hikurangi\n| page =13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20047\n| date = 1928-09-10\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280910.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Ponsonby||17 || Hikurangi ||14 ||Carlaw Park \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 15 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Game at Hikurangi\n| page =14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIX| issue=220\n| date = 1928-09-17\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280917.2.139.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi||23 || Parnell ||6 ||Hikurangi ||400\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 6 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Roope Rooster Final/Marist Defeats Ponsonby/A Margin of Two Points\n| page =14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20071\n| date = 1928-10-08\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281008.2.167.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| North Auckland||9 || Auckland Selection ||33 ||Whangarei ||1,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 13 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Hamilton V Northcote\n| page =16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20077\n| date = 1928-10-15\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281015.2.148.1\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref>\n|| Northcote ||5 || Hamilton || 3 ||Carlaw Park # 2, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 20 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Results\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20083\n| date = 1928-10-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281022.2.153.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Mount Albert 3rd Grade ||5 || Huntly Juniors || 15 ||Carlaw Park # 1, 1pm\n|-\n|}\n\n==Representative Fixtures and Trials==\nThe first representative fixture of the season was played against [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] for the Northern Union Challenge Cup which the visitors had won from [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] in 1927. [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] won the 1928 match by 22 points to 3. The game was played in poor weather and was notable for the number of serious injuries with S. Prentice of [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] breaking his nose, W. Smith of [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]] suffering a severe back injury, and S. Raynor of [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]] breaking his ribs. All three of them were taken to [[Auckland Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Football Accidents\n| page = 13\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIX| issue=142\n| date = 1928-06-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280618.2.116.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref> A midweek trial match was played between the Possibles and Probables in order to select the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team which was due to play the touring England side later in the season.\n\n[[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] trounced [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] in a Northern Union Cup match by 66 points to 22 with winger S. Hardgrave ([[Newton Rangers|Newton]]) running in five tries. The match was played in good conditions for the most part and was witnessed by an enormous crowd of around 15,000.\n\nA North Island v South Island trial match was played at [[Carlaw Park]]. The North Island team fielded a large contingent of Auckland players including [[Craddock Dufty]], Hardgrave, [[Hec Brisbane]], Wetherill, Prentice, [[Frank Delgrosso]], A. Scott, Hutt, Somers, and J. O\u2019Brien. The North Island team was far too good, winning 44 to 8.\n\nThe following week a Probables v Possibles match was played as part of the selection process for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team to play against the touring [[England national rugby league team|England]] side. The two teams featured the following Auckland players (Probables): [[Craddock Dufty]], L. Scott, Brisbane, Seagar, Peckham, [[Wally Somers]], Jim O\u2019Brien, Hall, A. Scott, (Possibles): Beattie, Hanlon, and Cleaver.\n\nThe final match of the season saw [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] go down to [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] both physically and on the scoreboard by 21 points to 7. The [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team was below strength.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1928 Auckland Representative Fixtures and Trials\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Northern Union Challenge Cup\n| 16 June <ref>{{c