nd || 44 || South Island || 8 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||10,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Possibles v Probables Match\n| 1 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Probables Beat Possibles/Candidates For First Test/Good Performance by Blazey\n| page = 13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20014\n| date = 1928-10-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280802.2.129\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref>\n|| Probables || 27 || Possibles || 24 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | England Tour Match\n| 7 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Province Beaten/Fourteen Points to Nine/Local Five-Eighths Weak\n| page = 12\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20020\n| date = 1928-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280809.2.118\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Auckland Provincial Team || 9 || England || 14 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||15,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | England Tour Match\n| 11 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Team Beaten/26 Points Against 15/Local Thirteen Tires/Visitors\u2019 Bright Passing\n| page = 12\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20023\n| date = 1928-08-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280813.2.124\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 15 || England || 26 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||25,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Northern Union Challenge Cup\n| 15 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Defeats Otago/Forty-Two Points to 22/Challenge Cup Retained\n| page = 12\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20053\n| date = 1928-09-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280917.2.125\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 42 || Otago || 22 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||6,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Inter-Provincial Match\n| 15 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title = Stormont Shield Contest\n| page = 18\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20079\n| date = 1928-10-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281017.2.158.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| South Auckland || 21 || Auckland || 7 || Huntly\n|-\n|}\n\n==Auckland Players Selected for New Zealand==\nThe following Auckland players were selected in the New Zealand team to play the first test versus England at [[Carlaw Park]].\n[[Craddock Dufty|C. Dufty]] (Newton), R. Hardgrave (Newton), C. List (Kingsland), L. Scott (Devonport), M. Wetherill (City), S. Prentice (Richmond), [[Frank Delgrosso|F. Delgrosso]] (Ponsonby), L. Hutt (Ponsonby), W. Somers (Newton), J. O\u2019Brien (Marist), Reserves: T. Peckham (Ponsonby), and T. Hall (Newton). New Zealand won the test by 17 points to 13 in front of 27,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Win for New Zealand/Seventeen to Thirteen/Great Tackling Witnessed/Dominion\u2019s Fine Forwards\n| page = 12\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=20017\n| date = 1928-08-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280806.2.107\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref> Brisbane who had not been considered for the first test due to injury was selected for the second test to be played in Dunedin and replaced L. Scott in the side.\n\n==Annual General Meetings and Club News==\nDetails of annual club meetings were as follows, along with notable news during the season.\n*[[Akarana rugby league club|Akarana League Football Club]] held at Carlaw Park. They stated that the 1927 season had been successful with two of their three teams winning their grades.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Akarana Club\n| page = 12\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19900\n| date = 1928-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280320.2.141.3\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref>\n*[[City Rovers|City Rovers Football Club]] held at Carlaw Park. \n*[[North Shore Albions|Devonport United League Football Club]] held at the Buffalo Lodge Rooms on March 19. During the season Devonport asked the Devonport Domain Board for permission to use the football ground for a match on June 23 and for the authority to charge spectators for entry. Permission was granted provided the charge did not exceed 1 shilling.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport Domain Board\n| page = 16\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19980\n| date = 1928-06-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280623.2.148.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-10}}</ref>\n*[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie United League Football Club]] held at their training shed opposite the Ellerslie Railway Station on March 26.\n*[[Glen Eden rugby league team|Glen Eden]] At the Auckland Rugby League's weekly Management Committee meeting in April saw them decide to give financial assistance to the Glen Eden Club toward paying off its ground.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Management Committee/Appointment of Selectors\n| page = 15\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19932\n| date = 1928-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280428.2.144.8\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref>\n*[[Grafton Athletic|Grafton Athletic Rugby League Football Club]] held at Leys Institute in Ponsonby.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Grafton Club\u2019s Officers\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19898\n| date = 1928-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280317.2.135.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref>\n*[[Kingsland Rovers Football Club]] held at Buffalo Lodge Rooms on March 25.\n*[[Mangere United Football Club]] held at Cook's Hall on March 26. During the season W. Hapi the halfback of the Mangere senior team died after a short illness. The Mangere team wore white arm bands on the jerseys for their round 11 match at Carlaw Park against Grafton.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Prominent Player\u2019s Death/W. Hapi, of Mangere/A Clever Native Half-Back\n| page =16 \n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIX| issue=168\n| date = 1928-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280718.2.146.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref> \n*[[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]] held at Donovan's Gymnasium in Parnell.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Old Boys\u2019 Club/Annual Meeting Held\n| page = 13\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19896\n| date = 1928-03-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280315.2.155.3\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> \n*[[Mount Albert Lions|Mt Albert]] held their first ever meeting at St George's Hall in Mt Albert. It was decided that they would form a club in Mt Albert though they did no decide on a name at this time. They would enter teams in the third and fourth grades.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Formation of New Club\n| page = 15\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19914\n| date = 1928-04-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280405.2.152.14\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref> During the season Auckland Rugby League made a grant of \u00a33 to Mount Albert for a dressing shed.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Management Committee Meet/Earlier Start of Games/Another Player Reinstated\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIX| issue=139\n| date = 1928-06-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280614.2.114.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n*[[New Lynn League Football Club]] held at Foresters\u2019 Hall, New Lynn on March 28.\n*[[Newton Rangers|Newton Rangers Football Club]] held at Nairn's Tea Rooms on Karangahape Road.\n*[[Northcote Tigers|Northcote-Birkenhead Ramblers League Football Club]] held at Foresters\u2019 Hall, Birkenhead on March 22.\n*[[Parnell rugby league club|Parnell League Football Club]] held at Donovan's Gymnasium in Parnell.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Parnell Club\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19898\n| date = 1928-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280317.2.135.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> It was noted at the meeting that Parnell had lost its ground as the council was going to put roads through it. They were going to make arrangements to use the Auckland Domain for training purposes.\n*[[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier League Football Club]] held in the Point Chevalier Hall.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Akarana Club\n| page = 12\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19900\n| date = 1928-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280320.2.141.3\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> \n*[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United Football Club]] held at The Leys Institute in Ponsonby. Ponsonby were being called \u201cPonies\u201d in the newspapers during the season. Ponsonby played the newly formed Hikurangi during the season and also toured the area with a senior and junior team.\n*[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers Football Club]] became the first team to play a rugby league match in Northland when they met the Hikurangi side.\n*Auckland Rugby League Primary Schools\u2019 Management Committee.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Primary Schools\n| page = 14\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXV| issue=19904\n| date = 1928-03-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280324.2.140.9\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> It was stated that eight teams were entered in various competitions in 1927.\n*Junior Management Committee held at Gray's Buildings on March 27.\n*Referees Association held at the League Rooms on March 26. During the season they asked that a written report submitted by its members should suffice for players ordered from the field, rather than requiring them to attend judicial inquiries as it was difficult to attend.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Management Committee Meet/Earlier Start of Games/Another Player Reinstated\n| page = 14\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIX| issue=139\n| date = 1928-06-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280614.2.114.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:Rugby league in Auckland]]\n[[Category:Rugby league governing bodies in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Rugby league]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1928_Auckland_Rugby_League_season"}
{"title_page": "List of children's hospitals in the United States", "text_new": "A [[children's hospital]] is a hospital that offers its services exclusively to children and adolescents. Most children's hospitals can serve children from birth up to the age of 21. The number of children's hospitals proliferated in the 20th century, as pediatric medical and surgical specialties separated from internal medicine and adult surgical specialties.\n\nChildren's hospitals are characterized by greater attention to the psychosocial support of children and their families. Some children and young people have to spend relatively long periods in the hospital, so having access to play and teaching staff can also be an important part of their care. With local partnerships, this can include trips to local botanical gardens, the zoo, and public libraries, for instance.\n\nIn addition to psychosocial support, children's hospitals have the added benefit of being staffed by professionals who are trained in treating children. A medical doctor that undertakes vocational training in pediatrics must also be accepted for membership by a professional college before they can practice pediatrics. While many normal hospitals can treat children adequately, pediatric specialists may be a better choice when it comes to treating rare afflictions that may prove fatal or severely detrimental to young children, in some cases before birth. Also, many children's hospitals will continue to see children with rare illnesses into adulthood, allowing for a continuity of care.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Hospital\n!City\n!State\n!Beds<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.childrenshospitals.org/Directories/Hospital-Directory|title=Children's Hospital Directory|website=www.childrenshospitals.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n![[Trauma center|Pediatric Trauma Level]]\n![[Neonatal intensive care unit|NICU]] Rating<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aap.org/en-us/advocacy-and-policy/aap-health-initiatives/nicuverification/Pages/NICUSearch.aspx|title=NICUSearch|website=AAP.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n!# Specialties Nationally Ranked<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/children|title=Find a Children's Hospital|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. News & World Report|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Children's of Alabama]]\n|[[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]]\n|[[Alabama]]\n|341\n|Level I Pediatric<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/aths/trauma-center-levels.html|title=Trauma Centers {{!}} Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH)|website=www.alabamapublichealth.gov|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n|3\n|6\n|-\n|[[Huntsville Hospital System|Huntsville Hospital for Women and Children]]\n|[[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]]\n|Alabama\n|51\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[University of South Alabama|USA Children's and Women's Hospital]]\n|[[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]]\n|Alabama\n|138\n|\n|3\n|\n|-\n|[[The Children's Hospital at Providence]]\n|[[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n|[[Alaska]]\n|114\n|Level II Pediatric\n|3\n|\n|-\n|[[Arkansas Children's Hospital]]\n|[[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]]\n|[[Arkansas]]\n|336\n|Level I Pediatric\n|4\n|5\n|-\n|[[Cardon Children's Medical Center]]\n|[[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]]\n|[[Arizona]]\n|162\n|\n|3\n|\n|-\n|[[Phoenix Children's Hospital]]\n|[[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n|[[Arizona]]\n|381\n|Level I Pediatric\n|3\n|10\n|-\n|Children's Center at [[Sutter Medical Center]]\n|[[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]]\n|[[California]]\n|121\n|\n|3\n|\n|-\n|[[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]]\n|[[Los Angeles]]\n|California\n|401\n|Level I Pediatric\n|4\n|10\n|-\n|[[Children's Hospital of Orange County (CHOC)|Children's Hospital of Orange County]]\n|[[Mission Viejo, California|Mission Viejo]]\n|California\n|316\n|Level II Pediatric\n|3\n|6\n|-\n|[[Lauren Small Children's Center at Bakersfield Memorial Hospital]]\n|[[Bakersfield]]\n|California\n|74\n|Level I Pediatr