es]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202084848/http://www.interactive.org/awards/2011_14th_awards.asp |archivedate=February 2, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' remembered Rob Wiethoff's voice acting performance as the second best in a video game.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/04/the-25-greatest-voice-acting-performances-in-video-games/rob-wiethoff |last=Hester |first=Larry |magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |title=The 25 Greatest Voice Acting Performances In Video Games |date=April 14, 2013 |accessdate=October 13, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Network World]]'' stated John \"is a complicated character, having been a bad person who is trying to make things right.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.networkworld.com/community/node/63194 |title=Red Dead Redemption Review: Saddle Up, Partners! |last=Shaw |first=Keith |date=July 2, 2010 |accessdate=July 26, 2013 |work=[[Network World]]}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated that \"[John] and his creators conjure such a convincing, cohesive and enthralling re-imagination of the real world that it sets a new standard for sophistication and ambition in electronic gaming.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/17/arts/television/17dead.html |title=Video Game Review - 'Red Dead Redemption' Brings Old West to Life |last=Schiesel |first=Seth |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 16, 2010 |accessdate=July 26, 2013}}</ref> Marston has been included in multiple lists of top video game character traits.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L1Z0SlaN-eY |title=Top 10 Beards in Gaming |publisher=[[YouTube]] |author=[[Machinima.com]] |date=April 14, 2011 |accessdate=August 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ugo.com/movies/best-gunslingers-john-marston |title=Best Gunslingers |author=Jensen, K. Thor |date=February 22, 2012 |publisher=[[UGO Networks]] |accessdate=August 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113160846/http://www.ugo.com/movies/best-gunslingers-john-marston |archivedate=November 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/top-100-video-game-heroes/ |title=100 best heroes in video games |date= |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/top-7-most-badass-game-characters-generation/ |title=The Top 7... Most badass game characters of the generation |date=September 28, 2012 |author=Cooper, Hollander |publisher=GamesRadar |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/01/the-50-most-badass-video-game-characters-of-all-time/john-marston |title=The 50 Most Badass Video Game Characters Of All Time |author=Avellan, Drea |date=February 1, 2013 |work=Complex |accessdate=August 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/02/25-of-the-most-realistic-video-game-romances/red-dead-redemption |title=The 25 Most Realistic Video Game Romances |author=Armikhani, Justin |date=February 14, 2013 |work=Complex |accessdate=August 2, 2013}}</ref> GamesRadar placed the character fifth in their list of best game characters of the generation,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/best-game-characters-generation/ |title=Best game characters of the generation |publisher=GamesRadar |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> and [[GameSpy]] called John Marston a noticeable omission from the 2011 ''[[Guinness World Records Gamer's Edition]]''{{'}}s top 50 video game characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.gamespy.com/articles/115/1150483p1.html |title=Guinness Ranks Your 50 Favorite Video Game Characters of All Time |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221072349/http://uk.gamespy.com/articles/115/1150483p1.html |archivedate=February 21, 2011 |author=Sharkey, Mike |date=February 16, 2011 |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |accessdate=May 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nCritics concurred that ''Red Dead Redemption'' was one of the best games of the [[History of video game consoles (seventh generation)|seventh generation era of video game consoles]].<ref name=\"Euro-Gen\"/> Dan Whitehead of [[Eurogamer]] wrote that he hoped the [[History of video game consoles (eighth generation)|eighth generation of consoles]] would offer \"similarly powerful experiences\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-10-22-games-of-the-generation-red-dead-redemption |title=Games of the Generation: Red Dead Redemption |last=Whitehead |first=Dan |website=[[Eurogamer]] |date=October 22, 2013 |accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref> [[IGN]] ranked the game third on its 2011 list of the top modern video games,<ref>{{cite web |author=IGN |url=http://au.ign.com/top/modern-games/3 |title=''Red Dead Redemption'' - #3 Top Modern Games |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=June 27, 2011 |accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref> and seventh on its 2014 list of the best games of the generation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://au.ign.com/top/games-of-a-generation/7 |title=Red Dead Redemption - #7 Top Games of a Generation |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref> [[GamesRadar]] listed ''Red Dead Redemption'' at second on its list of the best games of all time, in February 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/best-games-ever/ |title=The 100 best games of all time |last=GamesRadar Staff |first= |date=February 15, 2013 |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref> and sixth on its list of the best video game stories, in July 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/the-best-videogame-stories-ever/ |title=The best videogame stories ever |last=GamesRadar Staff |first= |date=July 12, 2013 |publisher=GamesRadar |accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref> In September 2013, the game was ranked the fifth best PlayStation 3 game,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2013/09/03/igns-top-25-playstation-3-games?page=3 |title=The Top 25 PS3 Games (3) |last1=Moriarty |first1=Colin |last2=Goldfarb |first2=Andrew |date=September 3, 2013 |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref> and the seventh best Xbox 360 game, by IGN.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2013/09/20/the-top-25-xbox-360-games-4?page=2 |title=The Top 25 Xbox 360 Games (2) |last=IGN Staff |first= |date=September 20, 2013 |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref> In November 2013, the game was ranked at fourth and eighth place on Eurogamer and ''Hardcore Gamer''{{'}}s list of the best games of the generation, respectively.<ref name=\"Euro-Gen\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-11-04-eurogamers-games-of-the-generation-the-top-50 |title=Eurogamer's Games of the Generation: The top 50 |last=Robinson |first=Martin |date=November 4, 2013 |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2013/11/08/the-top-ten-games-of-the-generation/60954/ |title=Top 100 Games of the Generation: The Top Ten Games of the Generation |author=HG Staff |date=November 8, 2013 |publisher=Hardcore Gamer |accessdate=November 14, 2013}}</ref> In January 2014, ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' ranked the game at number fifteen on its list of the best games of the generation.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/442793/cvgs-games-of-the-generation-20-1/ |title=CVG's Games of the Generation 20 - 1 |author=CVG Staff |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |date=January 1, 2014 |accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref> In June 2014, the game placed at number five on IGN's list of the \"Games of a Generation: Your Top 100\" as voted by readers of the site.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2014/06/04/games-of-a-generation-your-top-100-list?page=2 |title=Games of a Generation: Your Top 100 |author=IGN Staff |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=June 4, 2014 |accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref> In August 2014, the game placed seventh on ''[[Good Game (television series)|Good Game]]''{{'}}s Top 100 list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/goodgame/stories/s4065784.htm |title=Good Game Stories - Good Game Top 100 - Final List |author=''[[Good Game (television series)|Good Game]]'' |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=August 12, 2014 |accessdate=August 23, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822221642/http://www.abc.net.au/tv/goodgame/stories/s4065784.htm |archivedate=August 22, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[PlayStation Official Magazine \u2013 UK|PlayStation Official Magazine]]'' declared ''Red Dead Redemption'' the third best PlayStation 3 game of all time in March 2015.<ref>Hall of Fame listing, PlayStation Official Magazine issue 107, [[Future Publishing]], March 2015</ref> In July 2015, the game placed 10th on USgamer's The 15 Best Games Since 2000 list.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rignall |first1=Jaz |title=The 15 Best Games Since 2000, Number 10: Red Dead Redemption |url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-15-best-games-since-2000-10-red-dead-redemption |website=USgamer |publisher=Gamer Network |accessdate=July 29, 2015 |date=July 28, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729123357/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/the-15-best-games-since-2000-10-red-dead-redemption |archivedate=July 29, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Prequel===\nIn March 2013, Karl Slatoff, president of Take-Two Interactive, revealed that the company has an \"extensive pipeline of unannounced titles in development\" and mentioned that the ''Red Dead'' franchise was important to the company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/take-two-has-extensive-pipeline-of-unannounced-titles-in-development/1100-6404968/ |title=Take-Two has 'extensive pipeline' of unannounced titles in development |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=March 7, 2013 |accessdate=June 28, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109085419/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/take-two-has-extensive-pipeline-of-unannounced-titles-in-development/1100-6404968/ |archivedate=November 9, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Concept art for a future game in the series was reportedly leaked online in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2016/04/15/red-dead-redemption-2-map-leaked-will-be-a-prequel |title=Red Dead Redemption 2 Map Leaked, Will Be a Prequel |last=Passalacqua |first=Michael |date=April 15, 2016 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=June 28, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416071157/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/04/15/red-dead-redemption-2-map-leaked-will-be-a-prequel |archivedate=April 16, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> Images released by Rockstar in October 2016 sparked speculation regarding a sequel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/10/17/13304030/red-dead-redemption-images-shows-seven-silhouettes |title=New Red Dead Redemption image shows seven silhouettes |last=Crecente |first=Brian |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 17, 2016 |accessdate=October 18, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6lKpVQah2?url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/10/17/13304030/red-dead-redemption-images-shows-seven-silhouettes |archivedate=October 17, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/oct/17/red-dead-redemption-2-teasing-image-rockstar |title=Red Dead Redemption 2? Why people have gone crazy over a teasing image |last=Stuart |first=Keith |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=October 17, 2016 |accessdate=October 18, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6lKpWJnIf?url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/oct/17/red-dead-redemption-2-teasing-image-rockstar |archivedate=October 17, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> The game, ''[[Red Dead Redemption 2]]'', was announced by Rockstar that same month and was first released on the [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] on October 26, 2018.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hussain |first=Tamoor |title=Red Dead Redemption 2 Release Date Updated On PS4 And Xbox One |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/red-dead-redemption-2-release-date-updated-on-ps4-/1100-6456498/ |date=February 2, 2018 |access-date=February 3, 2018 |journal=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Mexico Gameplay\">Sources that compliment the usage of the song \"Far Away\" during gameplay include:\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2010/12/gaming-moments-of-2010-1-red-dead-redemption/ |title=Gaming Moments of 2010 #1: Red Dead Redemption |last=Serrels |first=Mark |work=[[Kotaku]] |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |date=December 24, 2010 |accessdate=December 9, 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.kotaku.com/5556788/my-highlight-of-red-dead-redemption-isthis-song |title=My Highlight Of Red Dead Redemption Is...This Song |last=Plunkett |first=Luke |work=[[Kotaku]] |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |date=June 8, 2010 |accessdate=December 9, 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/amazing-its-another-classic-gaming-moment-courtesy-of-rockstar/ |title=Amazing. It's another classic gaming moment, courtesy of Rockstar |last=Cundy |first=Matt |work=[[GamesRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=July 5, 2010 |accessdate=December 9, 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/red-dead-redemptions-most-perfect-moment-ruined-by-red-dead-redemption/ |title=Red Dead Redemption's most perfect moment, ruined by Red Dead Redemption |last=Houghton |first=David |work=[[GamesRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=July 9, 2010 |accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite web |last1=Hester |first1=Blake |title=How the Red Dead franchise began |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=October 17, 2018 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/10/17/17986118/how-the-red-dead-franchise-began-angel-studios-capcom-rockstar |language=en-US |accessdate=October 21, 2018}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.rockstargames.com/reddeadredemption/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1479962}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n{{Red Dead Redemption|state=expanded}}\n{{GDCA GOTY}}\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:2010 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Euphoria (software) games]]\n[[Category:Interactive Achievement Award winners]]\n[[Category:Motion capture in video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Red Dead]]\n[[Category:Rockstar Advanced Game Engine games]]\n[[Category:Rockstar Games]]\n[[Category:Take-Two Interactive games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 1911]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 1914]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games with downloadable content]]\n[[Category:Video games with expansion packs]]\n[[Category:Video games with time manipulation]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) video games]]\n[[Category:Works about atonement]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2010 action-adventure game}}\n{{For|the series|Red Dead}}\n{{Redirect|Grand Theft Horses|the 2018 graphic novel|Grand Theft Horse|horse theft in general|horse theft}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title      = Red Dead Redemption\n| image      = Red Dead Redemption.jpg\n| developer  = [[Rockstar San Diego]]{{efn|Additional work by [[Rockstar North]], [[Rockstar Leeds]] and [[Rockstar New England]].<ref>{{cite video game |title=Red Dead Redemption |developer=[[Rockstar San Diego]] |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date=May 18, 2010 |platform=[[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] |level=Credits}}</ref>}}\n| publisher  = [[Rockstar Games]]\n| director   = <!-- Blank because of Wikidata -->\n| producer   = {{Unbulleted list|Steve Martin|Josh Needleman|David Kunkler|John Ricchio}}\n| designer   = {{Unbulleted list|[[Christian Cantamessa]]|[[Leslie Benzies]]}}\n| programmer = Ted Carson\n| artist     = {{Unbulleted list|Joshua Bass|Daren Bader|George Davis|Nick Trifunovic}}\n| writer     = {{Unbulleted list|[[Dan Houser]]|Michael Unsworth|Christian Cantamessa}}\n| composer   = {{Unbulleted list|Bill Elm|[[Woody Jackson]]}}\n| series     = ''[[Red Dead]]''\n| engine     = [[Rockstar Advanced Game Engine|RAGE]]\n| platforms  = {{Unbulleted list|[[PlayStation 3]]|[[Xbox 360]]}}<!-- The game is emulated on PC, PS4 and Xbox One; they do not belong here. -->\n| released   = {{Video game release|NA|May 18, 2010|PAL|May 21, 2010}}\n| genre      = [[Action-adventure]]\n| modes      = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Red Dead Redemption''''' is a [[Western (genre)|Western]] [[action-adventure game]] developed by [[Rockstar San Diego]] and published by [[Rockstar Games]]. A [[spiritual successor]] to 2004's ''[[Red Dead Revolver]]'', it is the second game in the ''[[Red Dead]]'' series, and was released for the [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] in May 2010. ''Red Dead Redemption'' is set during the decline of the [[American frontier]] in the year 1911 and follows [[John Marston (Red Dead)|John Marston]], a former outlaw whose wife and son are taken hostage by the government in ransom for his services as a hired gun. Having no other choice, Marston sets out to bring three members of his former gang to justice.\n\nThe game is played from a [[Virtual camera system#Third-person view|third-person perspective]] in an [[open world]], allowing the player to interact with the game world at their leisure. The player can travel the virtual world, a fictionalized version of the [[Western United States]] and [[Mexico]], primarily by [[Equestrianism|horseback]] and on foot. Gunfights emphasize a [[gunslinger]] gameplay mechanic called \"[[Bullet time|Dead Eye]]\" that allows players to mark multiple shooting targets on enemies in slow motion. The game makes use of a morality system, by which the player's actions in the game affect their character's levels of honor and fame and how [[Non-player character|other characters]] respond to the player. An [[Multiplayer online game|online multiplayer]] mode is included with the game, allowing up to 16 players to engage in both [[cooperative gameplay|cooperative]] and competitive gameplay in a recreation of the single-player setting.\n\n''Red Dead Redemption'' was [[Development of Red Dead Redemption|developed]] over the course of five years and is one of the [[List of most expensive video games to develop|most expensive video games]] ever made. The game received critical acclaim for its visuals, dynamically-generated music, voice acting, gameplay, and story, and shipped over 15 million copies by 2017. It won several year-end accolades, including [[Game of the Year]] awards from several [[Video game journalism|gaming publications]], and is considered by critics as one of the [[List of video games considered the best|greatest video games ever made]]. After the game's release, several [[downloadable content]] additions were released; ''[[Red Dead Redemption: Undead Nightmare]]'', later released as a standalone game, added a new single-player experience in which Marston searches for a cure for an infectious [[Zombie apocalypse|zombie plague]] that has swept across the Old West. A ''Game of the Year Edition'' containing all additional content was released in October 2011. A prequel, ''[[Red Dead Redemption 2]]'', was released in October 2018 to similar acclaim.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Red Dead Redemption'' is a [[Western (genre)|Western]]-themed [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] game played from a [[Virtual camera system#Third-person view|third-person perspective]]. The player controls [[John Marston (Red Dead)|John Marston]] and completes missions, linear scenarios with set objectives, to progress through the story. Outside of missions, players may [[Nonlinear gameplay|freely roam]] the [[open world]]. The player can interact with the environment and engage in combat with enemies, using various firearms. Different breeds of horses are the main forms of transportation, each with different attributes. These horses must be tamed in order to use them. The player can utilize trains for quick travelling, but they can also stop the train by threatening or killing the passengers or driver. The game's undeveloped land makes up the largest portion of the game world, featuring various rugged and vast landscapes with occasional travelers, bandits, and wildlife. Urban settlements range from isolated farmhouses to crowded towns. Besides the American West, the player can also traverse a fictional Mexican state bordering the United States.<ref name=\"Manual\"/>\n\nIn addition to following the main storyline, the player will witness and can take part in random events they encounter as they explore the game world. These include public hangings, ambushes, pleas for assistance, encounters with strangers, ride-by shootings, and dangerous animal attacks. For example, if a group of people ride into town firing guns in the air, Marston can kill them, and will receive a bonus of honor and fame for protecting the town. The player can also take part in optional side activities, most of which give the player money. These side activities include dueling, in which the player must be a [[Fast Draw|faster draw]] than their opponent; bounty hunting, where Marston can hunt down bounties on [[wanted poster]]s; herb collecting, which involves gathering exotic plants from around the game map for town medics; gambling, where people can be found playing games such as poker and [[Knife game|Five Finger Fillet]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/11841/rockstar-game-tips-becoming-an-ace-online-poker-player-red-dead-.html |title=Rockstar Games Tips: Becoming an Ace Online Poker Player (Red Dead Redemption: Undead Nightmare Collection / Liars and Cheats Pack) |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |author=R* Y |date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=April 4, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"kotaku eyeson\">{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5272049/red-dead-redemption-eyes-on-impressions |title=Red Dead Redemption Eyes-On Impressions |website=Kotaku |date=May 28, 2009 |first=Michael |last=McWhertor |accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref> and hunting, in which the player can kill wild animals and skin their hides.<ref name=\"kotaku eyeson\" />\n\n''Red Dead Redemption'' makes use of a morality system where players have the ability to gain positive or negative honor.<ref name=\"Manual\" >{{cite book |author=[[Rockstar San Diego]] |title=Red Dead Redemption ''Game Manual'' |url=http://epix.xbox.com/shaXam/0201/55/78/5578b04b-140d-4a53-bc07-091cf1b372c5.PDF?v=1#rdr-en.PDF |accessdate=April 10, 2013 |year=2010 |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]]}}</ref> Honor can be gained by making morally positive choices, such as taking in an outlaw alive or saving a woman from a kidnapping. The player's overall honor standard is lowered for committing crimes or other negative choices. This works in conjunction with another system, fame, which affects how people react based on Marston's honor status. If Marston has little honor, [[non-player character]]s will feel insecure around them. If they have a high amount of honor, other characters will usually greet them and feel safe around them. They will also receive discounts in some stores, more pay for jobs and other bonuses.<ref name=\"Manual\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Cocker |first=Guy |url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/action/reddeadredemption/news.html?sid=6248188&mode=previews |title=Red Dead Redemption Hands-On\u2014Xbox 360 Previews at GameSpot |website=[[GameSpot]] |date=January 28, 2010 |accessdate=March 29, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601062455/http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/action/reddeadredemption/news.html?sid=6248188&mode=previews |archivedate=June 1, 2010}}</ref> A very low honor rating can result in a town's establishments closing their doors when Marston arrives. To combat this they can disguise themselves by wearing a [[bandana]] when performing criminal acts; alternatively, a very negative or criminal reputation warrants the player a large amount of respect and steep discounts from bandits and fencers at criminal hideouts, such as Thieves' Landing.<ref name=\"Manual\"/>\n\n=== Combat ===\n[[File:RedDeadRedemptionGameplay.jpg|thumb|left|''Red Dead Redemption'' features a [[cover system]] that lets the player hide behind objects and reach out to fire on people and animals.]]\nGunfights are a major gameplay mechanic in ''Red Dead Redemption''. The player can take cover, target a specific person or animal, [[blindfire]], and free aim. Individual body parts can also be targeted, in order to take targets down non-lethally. When the player shoots an enemy, the game engine uniquely creates the [[Artificial intelligence (video games)|AI]] reactions and movements depending on where they were hit. The player can choose from period-accurate weapons including revolvers, pistols, lever or bolt-action rifles, shotguns, sniper rifles, knives, explosives, lassos, mounted [[Gatling gun]]s, and cannons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/reddeadredemption/features/weapons/ |title=Features: Weapons |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date= |accessdate=March 29, 2010}}</ref> Duels utilize a [[gunslinger]] gameplay mechanic known as Dead Eye. Dead Eye is a targeting system that is used in a [[bullet time]]-like manner, allowing the player to slow down time to place a precise shot or paint in multiple shots. When the targeting sequence ends, Marston automatically fires to all marked locations in extremely quick succession.<ref name=\"Manual\"/>\n\nAdopted from the [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]], ''Red Dead Redemption'' has a modified wanted system. When the player commits a crime, such as killing people near witnesses, some will run to the nearest police station. The player can either bribe or kill them before they reach the station, negating any consequences. If a crime is committed near a lawman or constable, the wanted meter immediately appears along with a bounty count which increases with each crime committed. The higher the bounty, the more lawmen will be sent after the player. If they kill enough pursuers, then either [[United States Marshals Service|U.S. Marshals]] or the [[Mexican Army]], depending on their location, will be sent instead. To evade law enforcement in pursuit, the player must escape a circular zone until the wanted meter disappears. Alternatively, the player can kill all lawmen in a town to have the wanted meter disappear.<ref name=\"Manual\"/> Regardless of whether they escape capture, a bounty is placed upon the player which will cause bounty hunters to come after them in the wilderness. It is impossible to surrender to these bounty hunters by putting away the player's weapon and standing still as they will kill them regardless. Only lawmen in towns and [[Posse comitatus (common law)|posses]] will accept surrenders. The law will continue to chase the player, unless they pay their bounty at a [[Telegraphy|telegraph]] station or presents a pardon letter. When arrested, the player pays off their bounty, spends a certain number of days in jail depending on the severity of their crimes, and is then released. If the player does not have enough money to pay back the bounty, the law will assign bounty hunting activities to complete until enough money is earned.<ref name=\"Manual\"/>\n\n=== Multiplayer ===\n''Red Dead Redemption'' includes online multiplayer with a maximum of 16 players per session. Every multiplayer game, both free-for-all and team based, will begin with a [[Mexican standoff]]. Survivors of the standoff will be able to move to any part of the battlefield in preparation for respawning enemies. Crates in the environment contain extra weapons, ammo, and other [[powerup]]s. Players can level up and complete weapon challenges which earn them rewards such as new character models, golden weapon skins, new titles, and new breeds of [[Riding animal|animal mounts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2010/04/08/red-dead-redemption-online-free-roam-multiplayer-revealed/ |title=Red Dead Redemption's online 'Multiplayer Free Roam' revealed |first=Andrew |last=Yoon |publisher=Joystiq |accessdate=April 8, 2010 |date=April 8, 2010}}</ref> Additional multiplayer modes were added via [[downloadable content]] (DLC). Stronghold is an attack or defend scenario, with teams switching roles as the round ends. It is included in the ''Liars and Cheats'' pack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-08-27-red-deads-liars-and-cheats-pack-dated |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=April 10, 2013 |date=August 27, 2012 |first=Tom |last=Bramwell |title=Red Dead's Liars and Cheats Pack dated}}</ref> The ''[[Red Dead Redemption: Undead Nightmare|Undead Nightmare]]'' pack included two new games modes: Undead overrun mode, and Land Grab. It also included eight new [[zombie (fictional)|zombie]] characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-10-22-rockstar-details-rdrs-land-grab-mode |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=April 10, 2013 |date=October 22, 2010 |first=Wesley |last=Yin-Poole |title=Rockstar details RDR's Land Grab Mode}}</ref>\n\nThe free-for-all and team versions of Shootout mode both follow a traditional [[Deathmatch (gaming)|deathmatch]] scenario where players or teams must accumulate the most kills. Many [[capture the flag]] variants are also available. Hold Your Own is a traditional mode where each team has to defend their bag of gold from the enemy team whilst capturing the other. Grab The Bag has both teams attacking one bag placed in a section of the map. Gold Rush is a free-for-all variant, trying to grab and keep as many bags as possible. The multiplayer portion ''Red Dead Redemption'' also features open world gameplay.<ref name=\"Manual\"/> All players in the server can form or join a group of other players, known as a posse, of up to eight players and take part in activities such as hunting or attacking computer-controlled gang hideouts or another player's posse.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/reddeadredemption/news/article/4551/watch_%22multiplayer_free_roam%22_-_the_new_red_dead_redemption_gameplay_series_video |title=Multiplayer in Red Dead Redemption |author=R* Q |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |accessdate=April 8, 2010 |date=April 8, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815181821/http://www.rockstargames.com/reddeadredemption/restricted_content/restricted_content_agegated/ref?redirect=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.rockstargames.com%2Freddeadredemption%2Fnews%2Farticle%2F4551%2Fwatch_%2522multiplayer_free_roam%2522_-_the_new_red_dead_redemption_gameplay_series_video&hash=f33b1b6b71417d64b121e63bd2c6b0e4 |archive-date=August 15, 2017}}</ref> In some game modes, players are unable to kill other players.<ref name=\"Friendly Free Roam\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/10151/friendly-free-roam-coming-very-soon-to-red-dead-redemption-multi.html |title=Friendly Free Roam, Coming Very Soon to Red Dead Redemption Multiplayer |author=R* Q |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date=October 8, 2010 |accessdate=October 18, 2016}}</ref>{{efn|name=\"Friendly\"|Rockstar addressed the game's [[Griefer|griefing]] problem by introducing a Friendly Free Roam in an update on October 23, 2010.<ref name=\"Friendly Free Roam\"/>}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n===Setting===\n''Red Dead Redemption'' spans New Austin and West Elizabeth, two [[List of fictional states of the United States|fictitious states of the United States]], as well as Nuevo Paraiso, a fictitious Mexican state. New Austin and West Elizabeth are adjacent to each other and share a southern border with Mexico. Nuevo Paraiso is a Mexican state, separated from U.S. territory by the San Luis River. The game takes place primarily in the year 1911, featuring the final decade of the [[American frontier]] and the cowboy and outlaw archetypes that shaped it. The landscape of the Wild West is beginning to fade and modern technologies like automobiles, machine guns, and oil drilling projects are beginning to appear.\n\n===Plot===\n{{See also|List of Red Dead Redemption characters}}\nThe game begins in 1911, where former outlaw John Marston ([[Rob Wiethoff]]) is taken from his family by [[Bureau of Investigation]] agents Edgar Ross (Jim Bentley) and his partner, Archer Fordham ([[David Wilson Barnes]]), and will only be granted amnesty when he brings the remaining members of his old gang to justice. John is escorted to the town of Armadillo and sets off to track down former ally Bill Williamson ([[Steve J. Palmer]]). He confronts Williamson and his men at their stronghold, Fort Mercer, only to be shot and left for dead. Local rancher Bonnie MacFarlane (Kimberly Irion) finds him critically wounded and takes him to her ranch for recovery. Several days later, John begins performing tasks and favors for various allies in exchange for their help with organizing an attack on Fort Mercer. John and his group then breach the fort and defeat Williamson's gang only to find that Williamson has fled to Mexico to seek help from Javier Escuella (Antonio Jaramillo), another former member of John's gang.\n\nIn Mexico, John initially sides with Mexican Army Colonel Agust\u00edn Allende (Gary Carlos Cervantes) to help end a rebellion in return for Allende delivering Escuella and Williamson to him. However, Allende betrays John, who then sides with the rebels. John, along with rebel leader Abraham Reyes ([[Josh Segarra]]), eventually turns the tide in favor of the rebels, launching an assault on the El Presidio fortress. They find Escuella, who attempts to bargain for his life by revealing that Williamson has been under Allende's protection. John is given the option to either kill Escuella or turn him over to the Bureau. John and Reyes then take the fight to Allende. As Allende's palace is stormed by the rebels, both he and Williamson flee but are apprehended and killed. Reyes takes charge of the local government and plans to advance on the capital, while John leaves to meet with the Bureau in Blackwater.\n\nRoss and Fordham refuse to let John return to his family until he assists the Bureau in hunting down the only remaining member of his previous gang who is still active as an outlaw: its leader and John's surrogate father, Dutch van der Linde ([[Benjamin Byron Davis]]). After surviving several ambushes and thwarting a bank robbery, John joins Ross, Fordham, and a group of U.S. soldiers in an attack on Dutch's hideout. During the assault, John chases Dutch up to a cliff, where the latter, mortally wounded, warns John that the Bureau won't let him have peace and then commits suicide by backing off the cliff.\n\nJohn is released from his deal and returns home to his wife Abigail (Sophie Marzocchi) and son Jack ([[Josh Blaylock]]). John devotes his time tending to the ranch, having sworn to keep himself and his family away from the outlaw lifestyle forever. However, true to Dutch's word, Ross double-crosses John and leads a combined force of soldiers, lawmen, and government agents after him. John fends off several waves of attackers and gets his family to safety, but stays behind to hold back the rest. Despite a valiant last stand, he dies after being shot numerous times by Ross and his men and is buried by his family on the hill overlooking the ranch.\n\nThree years later in 1914, following the death of his mother, Jack tracks down the now-retired Ross and kills him in a duel, avenging his father and continuing the path of violence his father had tried to keep away from him. The fates of John's companions are later summarized in newspaper articles and NPC dialog: Marshal Leigh Johnson retired from Armadillo at age 54 and moved away, Reyes was consumed by power and became a tyrant, Bonnie MacFarlane eventually married, Irish shot himself dead in an outhouse when his gun accidentally discharged, Seth Briars eventually found treasure and became rich, and Landon Ricketts died quietly in his sleep.\n\n==Development==\n{{Main|Development of Red Dead Redemption}}\n\n[[Rockstar San Diego]] began to [[Development of Red Dead Redemption|develop ''Red Dead Redemption'']] in 2005. Development was conducted by a team of more than 800 people, including Rockstar San Diego's core team and staff from parent company [[Rockstar Games]]' studios around the world.<ref name=\"winning\">{{cite web |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/246697/red-dead-redemption-gets-another-winning-review/ |title=News: Red Dead Redemption gets another winning review |last=Ingham |first=Tim |work=[[Computer and Video Games]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=May 16, 2010 |accessdate=June 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SKk9lFoh?url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/246697/red-dead-redemption-gets-another-winning-review/ |archivedate=September 4, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The game runs on the proprietary [[Rockstar Advanced Game Engine]] (RAGE), which was improved for the game to improve its [[draw distance]] rendering capabilities.<ref name=\"Cantamessa\">{{cite magazine |url=http://gamefanmag.com/features/interview-christian-cantamessa-red-dead-redemption |title=Interview: Christian Cantamessa \u2013 Red Dead Redemption |last=Cabral |first=Matt |magazine=[[GameFan]] |date=April 7, 2010 |accessdate=September 26, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Ss5fU2J1?url=http://gamefanmag.com/features/interview-christian-cantamessa-red-dead-redemption |archivedate=September 26, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Euphoria (software)|Euphoria]] and [[Bullet (software)|Bullet]] software handle additional animation and rendering tasks.<ref name=\"Q&A\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/red-dead-redemption-exclusive-qanda/1100-6249985/ |title=Red Dead Redemption Exclusive Q&A |author=Staff |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=February 11, 2010 |accessdate=August 29, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SAnbUFtg?url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/red-dead-redemption-exclusive-qanda/1100-6249985/ |archivedate=August 28, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Having exhausted the use of [[History of video game consoles (sixth generation)|previous hardware]] on previous projects, Rockstar felt inspired after realising the potential power of the [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]].<ref name=\"AMaHH1\">{{cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2009/05/09/red-dead-redemption-a-man-and-his-horse |title=Red Dead Redemption: A Man and His Horse |page=1 |last=Onyett |first=Charles |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 24, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Sp0RY2Fo?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/09/red-dead-redemption-a-man-and-his-horse |archivedate=September 24, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Analyst estimations place the game's combined development and marketing budget between US$80 million and US$100 million, which would make it one of the [[List of most expensive video games to develop|most expensive video games]] ever made.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/17/arts/television/17dead.html |title=Video Game Review - 'Red Dead Redemption' Brings Old West to Life |last=Schiesel |first=Seth |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |date=May 16, 2010 |accessdate=September 4, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228003055/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/17/arts/television/17dead.html |archivedate=February 28, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe open world was created to represent iconic features of the American frontier. Key members of the game world product team took research trips to [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] and the [[Library of Congress]] in their extensive research on the American frontier.<ref name=\"AMaHH3\">{{cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2009/05/09/red-dead-redemption-a-man-and-his-horse?page=3 |title=Red Dead Redemption: A Man and His Horse |page=3 |last=Onyett |first=Charles |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 24, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006095526/http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/09/red-dead-redemption-a-man-and-his-horse?page=3 |archivedate=October 6, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> They also captured a multitude of photographs, and analyzed various classic [[Western (genre)|Western]] films.<ref name=\"Q&A\"/> The team considered creating the open world one of the most technically demanding aspect of the game's production, in terms of filling the world with enough content to interest players.<ref name=\"AMaHH2\">{{cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2009/05/09/red-dead-redemption-a-man-and-his-horse?page=2 |title=Red Dead Redemption: A Man and His Horse |page=2 |last=Onyett |first=Charles |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 24, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006081428/http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/09/red-dead-redemption-a-man-and-his-horse?page=2 |archivedate=October 6, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The team chose 1911 as the game's setting as they felt that exploring the transformation from \"the old West\" into a modern world was intriguing.<ref name=\"Cantamessa\"/> The team viewed ''Red Dead Redemption'' as a [[spiritual successor]] to ''[[Red Dead Revolver]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=James |first1=Dean |title=Five Years Later, Where Is Red Dead Redemption 2? |url=http://attackofthefanboy.com/opinion/five-years-later-where-is-red-dead-redemption-2/ |website=Attack of the Fanboy |publisher=Modern Media Group LLC |accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref> and designed it to improve upon the gameplay mechanics. They sought to maintain the shooting mechanic and expand on other game features, attempting to achieve realism with every feature of the game.<ref name=\"Q&A\"/> In particular, the team faced a challenge in creating realistic movement for the horse, resulting in the engagement of a stunt horse to simulate movement for the designers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/breaking-in-the-digital-horses-of-red-dead-redemption/1100-6261863/ |title=Breaking in the Digital Horses of Red Dead Redemption |author=GameSpot Staff |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=May 10, 2010 |accessdate=October 5, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T5oXHtUl?url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/breaking-in-the-digital-horses-of-red-dead-redemption/1100-6261863/ |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter an audition process, [[Rob Wiethoff]] was selected to portray John Marston.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/features/2013/6/19/4406600/small-town-man-John-Marston |title=What happened to John Marston |last=Stafford |first=Patrick |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=June 19, 2013 |accessdate=September 14, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Sp79ewFK?url=http://www.polygon.com/features/2013/6/19/4406600/small-town-man-John-Marston |archivedate=September 24, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The cast's performances were mostly recorded using [[motion capture]] technology, with additional dialogue and sound effects recorded in a [[Recording studio|studio]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nave360.com/rob-wietoff-aka-john-marston-nave360-interview/ |title=Rob Wietoff (AKA John Marston) Nave360 Interview |last=Murray |first=Charlie |publisher=Nave360 |date=January 4, 2011 |accessdate=October 5, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T5NxsfQE?url=http://www.nave360.com/rob-wietoff-aka-john-marston-nave360-interview/ |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Red Dead Redemption'' also features [[Red Dead Redemption Original Soundtrack|an original score]], which was composed by Bill Elm and [[Woody Jackson]], collaborating with each other over fifteen months.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2010/may/26/red-dead-redemption-soundtrack |title=Redemption songs: the making of the Red Dead Redemption soundtrack |last=Stuart |first=Keith |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=May 26, 2010 |accessdate=August 17, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SKkJg4b9?url=http://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2010/may/26/red-dead-redemption-soundtrack |archivedate=September 4, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Rockstar also consulted musicians who played traditional Western instruments, such as [[harmonica]] player [[Tommy Morgan]].<ref name=\"makingof sountrack\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/7361/behind-the-scenes-of-the-red-dead-redemption-soundtrack.html |title=Behind the Scenes of the Red Dead Redemption Soundtrack |author=R* Q |work=Rockstar Newswire |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date=July 28, 2010 |accessdate=October 5, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T67bphX5?url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/7361/behind-the-scenes-of-the-red-dead-redemption-soundtrack.html |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThough a [[technology demonstration]] was shown in 2005,<ref name=\"Old West Project\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cLE1oRjxyJA |title=Red Dead Redemption 2005 Teaser |author=[[Rockstar Games]] |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=May 26, 2007 |accessdate=May 12, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620124511/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cLE1oRjxyJA |archivedate=June 20, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Red Dead Redemption'' was first formally announced by Rockstar Games on February 3, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2009/02/04/red-dead-redemption-announced |title=Red Dead Redemption Announced |first=Martin |last=Robinson |website=[[IGN]] |date=February 4, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SKgReCtO?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/02/04/red-dead-redemption-announced |archivedate=September 4, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The debut trailer was released on May 6, 2009, introducing the game's protagonist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2009/05/08/five-reasons-to-love-red-dead-redemption |title=Five Reasons to Love Red Dead Redemption |last=Goldstein |first=Hilary |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=June 5, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619074727/http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/08/five-reasons-to-love-red-dead-redemption |archivedate=June 19, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The game missed its original projected April 2010 release date, pushed back to May 18, 2010 to allow for further polishing.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jackson |first=Mike |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/237608/red-dead-redemption-delayed-to-may/ |title=News: Red Dead Redemption delayed to May |publisher=[[Computer And Video Games]] |date=March 4, 2010 |accessdate=June 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SKgky2Rg?url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/237608/red-dead-redemption-delayed-to-may/ |archivedate=September 4, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> To spur [[pre-order]] game sales, Rockstar collaborated with several retail outlets to provide pre-order bonuses. These included exclusive in-game outfits, weapons and horses,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/3261/red-dead-redemption-exclusive-preorder-bonuses-the-referendum-th.html |title=Red Dead Redemption Exclusive Pre-Order Bonuses: The Referendum, The Golden Guns, The War Horse and More |author=R* Q |work=Rockstar Newswire |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date=February 9, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SKj86FuP?url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/3261/red-dead-redemption-exclusive-preorder-bonuses-the-referendum-th.html |archivedate=September 4, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> as well as the game's official soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/15141/red-dead-redemption-deadly-assassin-outfit-golden-guns-weapon-pa.html |title=Red Dead Redemption: Deadly Assassin Outfit, Golden Guns Weapon Pack and War Horse Now Available on Xbox LIVE and PlayStation Network |author=R* Q |work=Rockstar Newswire |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date=April 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 4, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SKjBPVDq?url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/15141/red-dead-redemption-deadly-assassin-outfit-golden-guns-weapon-pa.html |archivedate=September 4, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Additional content===\n{{See also|Undead Nightmare}}\nPost-release content was added to ''Red Dead Redemption'' as [[downloadable content]] (DLC) packs. ''Outlaws to the End'', released on June 22, 2010, added six new cooperative side missions for the game's multiplayer. The Legends and Killers pack was released on August 10, 2010; it added eight multiplayer characters from ''Red Dead Revolver'', nine map locations, and a [[Tomahawk (axe)|Tomahawk]] weapon. The Liars and Cheats pack was released on September 21, 2010; it added competitive multiplayer modes and mini-games, additional characters from the single-player game and the Explosive Rifle weapon.<ref name=\"kotaku-DLC packs\">{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5582371/red-dead-redemption-adding-zombies-multiplayer-poker-more |title=Red Dead Redemption Adding Zombies, Multiplayer Poker, More |last=Totilo |first=Stephen |work=[[Kotaku]] |publisher=[[Gawker Media]] |date=July 8, 2010 |accessdate=April 10, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T5d8ydS1?url=http://kotaku.com/5582371/red-dead-redemption-adding-zombies-multiplayer-poker-more |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Hunting and Trading pack was released on October 12, 2010; it added a [[jackalope]] to the game's world, and some additional outfits.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/9901/free-hunting-and-trading-outfits-pack-for-red-dead-redemption-co.html |title=Free Hunting and Trading Outfits Pack for Red Dead Redemption Coming October 12th |author=R* Q |work=Rockstar Newswire |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date=October 5, 2010 |accessdate=October 6, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T5dCT9nU?url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/9901/free-hunting-and-trading-outfits-pack-for-red-dead-redemption-co.html |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Red Dead Redemption: Undead Nightmare|Undead Nightmare]]'', released on October 26, 2010, added a new single-player campaign with ghost towns and cemeteries full of zombies; in the game's story, players continue to assume control of John Marston as he searches for a cure to the zombie outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/red-dead-redemption-undead-nightmare-hands-on/ |title=Red Dead Redemption \u2013 Undead Nightmare hands-on |last=Reparaz |first=Mikel |work=[[GamesRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=October 14, 2010 |accessdate=October 15, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T5cyyTGT?url=http://www.gamesradar.com/red-dead-redemption-undead-nightmare-hands-on/ |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Myths and Mavericks pack, released for free on September 13, 2011, added additional characters from the single-player campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/16621/free-fan-appreciation-dlc-for-red-dead-coming-soon.html |title=FREE Fan Appreciation DLC for Red Dead Coming Soon |author=R* Y |work=Rockstar Newswire |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date=June 6, 2011 |accessdate=June 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T5dGBeGf?url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/16621/free-fan-appreciation-dlc-for-red-dead-coming-soon.html |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/18701/release-date-details-on-the-free-red-dead-redemption-myths-and-m.html |title=Release Date & Details on the Free Red Dead Redemption Myths and Mavericks Bonus Pack |author=R* S |work=Rockstar Newswire |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date=September 1, 2011 |accessdate=June 17, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T5dIMqyD?url=http://www.rockstargames.com/newswire/article/18701/release-date-details-on-the-free-red-dead-redemption-myths-and-m.html |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA ''Game of the Year Edition'' containing all downloadable content was released for both PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360, on October 11, 2011 in North America and on October 14, 2011 internationally.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ign.com/articles/2011/09/13/red-dead-goty-edition-this-fall |title=Red Dead GOTY Edition This Fall |last=Goldfarb |first=Andrew |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=September 14, 2011 |accessdate=October 5, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6T5dLzAE1?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/09/13/red-dead-goty-edition-this-fall |archivedate=October 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, Microsoft added the game to its [[List of Xbox 360 games compatible with Xbox One|backwards compatibility list for Xbox One]] platforms in July 2016.<ref name=\"Polygon: BC\">{{Cite web |last1=Frank |first1=Allegra |title=Red Dead Redemption will finally be backward compatible with Xbox One |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=July 5, 2016 |url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/7/5/12099272/red-dead-redemption-backward-compatibility-xbox-one |accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| title =\n| subtitle =\n| state = plain\n| width = 26em\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| MC = 95/100<ref name=\"MC PS3\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/red-dead-redemption |title=Red Dead Redemption for PlayStation 3 Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 3, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"MC 360\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/red-dead-redemption |title=Red Dead Redemption for Xbox 360 Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| 1UP = A<ref name=\"1up review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3179335&p=4 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120630040828/http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3179335&p=4 |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 30, 2012 |title=Red Dead Redemption Review |first=Scott |last=Sharkey |website=[[1UP.com|1UP]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref>\n| Edge = 10/10<ref name=edgeten>{{cite web |title=The ten amendments: we crown seven games from the last 20 years of Edge with a retrospective 10 |url=http://www.edge-online.com/features/the-ten-amendments-we-crown-seven-games-from-the-last-20-years-of-edge-with-a-retrospective-10/ |work=Edge Magazine |publisher=Future Publishing |accessdate=February 22, 2014}}</ref>{{efn|''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' originally gave the game 9/10,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.next-gen.biz/reviews/review-red-dead-redemption |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120908140006/http://www.next-gen.biz/reviews/review-red-dead-redemption |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 8, 2012 |title=Review: Red Dead Redemption |author=Edge Staff |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge Online]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 18, 2010}}</ref> but retroactively changed the score to 10/10.<ref name=\"edgeten\"/>}}\n| EuroG = 8/10<ref name=\"eurogamer review\">{{cite web |first=Simon |last=Parkin |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/red-dead-redemption-review |title=Red Dead Redemption Review |website=[[Eurogamer]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=October 4, 2010}}</ref>\n| GI = 9.75/10<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/red_dead_redemption/b/xbox360/archive/2010/05/17/review.aspx |title=Rockstar Wrangles The Best Video Game Western Of All Time |last=Bertz |first=Matt |work=[[Game Informer]] |publisher=[[GameStop]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref>\n| GamePro = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"gamepro review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/reviews/215190/red-dead-redemption/ |title=Red Dead Redemption review from GamePro |first=Will |last=Herring |magazine=[[GamePro]] |date=May 7, 2010 |accessdate=May 17, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522070357/http://www.gamepro.com/article/reviews/215190/red-dead-redemption/ |archivedate=May 22, 2010}}</ref>\n| GSpy = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"GameSpy Review\">{{cite web |url=http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/red-dead-redemption/1091233p1.html |title=Red Dead Redemption - Xbox 360 |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |date=May 19, 2010 |accessdate=May 19, 2010 |first=Will |last=Tuttle}}</ref>\n| GT = 9.5/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/video/review-hd-red-dead/100286 |title=News: Red Dead Redemption Review |publisher=[[GameTrailers]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 9.5/10<ref name=\"GSpotReview\">{{cite web |first=Justin |last=Calvert |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/red-dead-redemption-review/1900-6262899/ |title=Red Dead Redemption Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |date=May 18, 2010 |accessdate=June 19, 2012}}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.7/10<ref name=\"ign review\">{{cite web |last=Brudvig |first=Erik |url=https://ign.com/articles/2010/05/17/red-dead-redemption-review |title=Red Dead Redemption Review |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref>\n<!-- Removed reviews (can be used in prose)\n| G4 = 5/5<ref name=\"g4tv review\">{{cite web |url=http://g4tv.com/games/xbox-360/57148/Red-Dead-Redemption/review/ |title=Red Dead Redemption Review |first=Jake |last=Gaskill |publisher=[[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4TV]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 18, 2010}}</ref>\n| PALGN = 9/10<ref>{{cite web |first=Jeremy |last=Jastrzab |url=http://palgn.com.au/xbox-360/16470/red-dead-redemption-review/ |title=Red Dead Redemption Review - Xbox 360 Video Game Review - PAL Gaming Network |publisher=[[PALGN]] |date=May 30, 2010 |accessdate=June 19, 2012}}</ref>\n| Play = 92/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=246882&site=cvg |title=Review: Red Dead Redemption&nbsp;\u2014 PS3 Review |first=Andy |last=Hartup |publisher=[[Computer And Video Games]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=October 4, 2010}}</ref>\n| OXMUK = 9/10<ref name=GR>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.oxm.co.uk/19537/reviews/red-dead-redemption-review/ |title=Red Dead Redemption Review |magazine=[[Official Xbox Magazine|Official Xbox Magazine (UK)]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=June 19, 2012 |first=Mike |last=Channel}}</ref>\n| OPMUK = 10/10<ref>''PlayStation Official Magazine UK'', June 2010, p.107</ref> -->\n}}\n\n''Red Dead Redemption'' was released to critical acclaim. [[Review aggregator]] website [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Normalization (statistics)|normalized]] rating in the 0\u2013100 range, calculated an average score of 95 out of 100, indicating \"universal acclaim\", based on 73 reviews for the PlayStation 3 version and 96 reviews for the Xbox 360 version.<ref name=\"MC PS3\"/><ref name=\"MC 360\"/> Commercially, the game has also been very successful. By August 2011, the game had shipped over 11&nbsp;million copies, 2&nbsp;million of which were retail units of ''Undead Nightmare''.<ref name=\"sales11M\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/36447/TakeTwo_Red_Dead_Redemption_Ships_11M_Units.php |title=Take-Two: ''Red Dead Redemption'' Ships 11M Units |last=Graft |first=Kris |date=August 8, 2011 |website=[[Gamasutra]] |accessdate=August 10, 2011}}</ref> {{as of|2017|February|}}, ''Red Dead Redemption'' has shipped over 15 million units.<ref>{{cite web |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |title=Red Dead Redemption Shipped 15M Copies; Take-Two Promises Major Marketing For Sequel |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/red-dead-redemption-shipped-15m-copies-take-two-pr/1100-6447645/ |date=February 7, 2017 |accessdate=February 7, 2017 |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>\n\nMany critics praised the landscape, environment and graphics of ''Red Dead Redemption''. Erik Brudvig of [[IGN]] lauded the environmental details, noting the player can even scare a flock of birds from the bushes as they ride past. He also noted that the game's dynamic events, weather and ambient sounds provide a rich experience for players. He summarized by stating \"you can also expect a fantastic game that offers the Western experience we've all been waiting for.\"<ref name=\"ign review\" /> ''[[Game Informer]]'' called the scenery \"breathtaking\", and the cinematic cutscenes \"vastly improved\" over ''[[Grand Theft Auto IV]]'', and named it the \"best-looking Rockstar game to date\".<ref name=\"GI\"/>\n\n[[File:Red Dead Redemption - Gameplay.ogv|thumb|left|300px|thumbtime=0:16|The portion of the game in which Marston enters Mexico was acclaimed by critics and players. The usage of the song \"Far Away\" by [[Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez (singer)|Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez]] led to the scene being regarded as \"perfect\" and \"beautiful\" by gaming journalists.<ref name=\"Mexico Gameplay\"/> (0:30)|alt=Video sample of the game.]]\nThe music, sound and voice acting in the game was also widely praised and spoken about. It won the Best Original Music and Best Voice Acting awards from [[GameSpot]].<ref name=\"BOM\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=12 |title=Best Voice Acting - The Best Games of 2010 |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=April 9, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101217173354/http://www.gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=12 |archivedate=December 17, 2010}}</ref> When talking about the sound design of ''Red Dead Redemption'', ''Game Informer'' said \"From pitch-perfect gunshots to the daunting rumble of prairie thunderstorms, the remarkable attention to audio detail brings the world to life\".<ref name=\"GI\"/>\n\nCritics and reviewers spoke about the successful use of the game engine, and made similarities of the controls and physics to the [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]]. ''Game Informer'' said that Rockstar \"[transposed] the ''Grand Theft Auto'' gameplay template onto a Wild West setting\".<ref name=\"GI\"/> ''[[Good Game (television series)|Good Game]]'' reviewer [[Stephanie Bendixsen|Stephanie \"Hex\" Bendixsen]] said that \"[Rockstar] really looked at what people liked and didn't like in their game design from [''Grand Theft Auto IV''], and included it here\".<ref name=\"GG\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/goodgame/stories/s2914340.htm |title=Good Game stories&nbsp;\u2014 Red Dead Redemption |author=''[[Good Game (television series)|Good Game]]'' |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=May 31, 2010}}</ref> [[Eurogamer]]'s Simon Parkin felt ''Red Dead Redemption'' successfully \"re-clothes\" the ''[[Grand Theft Auto]]'' framework in an \"exciting, distinct and expertly realised scenario\".<ref name=\"eurogamer review\" />\n\nThe multiplayer aspect of ''Red Dead Redemption'' received mixed commentary from critics. ''[[GamePro]]''{{'}}s Will Herring praised the variety of multiplayer modes and the open gameplay, but noted that it put more responsibility on the players for keeping the game interesting.<ref name=\"gamepro review\" /> Justin Calvert of [[GameSpot]] also gave high marks for the game's variety of multiplayer modes, but felt that there was a lack in customization options for players.<ref name=\"GSpotReview\" /> In a more critical view of multiplayer, Scott Sharkey of [[1UP.com]] noted that games can suffer from [[Griefer|griefing]]{{efn|name=\"Friendly\"}} due to the open nature of multiplayer gameplay. He also criticized the [[Experience point|leveling]] and unlocking aspects, noting that \"The first few minutes spent as a toothless miner riding a balky mule can be pretty humiliating\".<ref name=\"1up review\" /> [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4TV]]'s Jake Gaskill echoed this sentiment. He noted that the game often [[Spawning (video game)|respawns]] players in a similar location to their death, which allows the killing player to repeatedly grief the other player.<ref name=\"g4tv review\">{{cite web |url=http://g4tv.com/games/xbox-360/57148/Red-Dead-Redemption/review/ |title=Red Dead Redemption Review |first=Jake |last=Gaskill |publisher=[[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4TV]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 18, 2010}}</ref> Rockstar has since added a feature which allows for players being griefed to transport to another area upon respawn.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/forums/read/7.216461-Rockstar-Bringing-New-Law-to-Red-Dead-Redemptions-Multiplayer |title=The Escapist: Forums: The News Room: Rockstar Bringing New Law to Red Dead Redemption's Multiplayer |accessdate=March 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\nSince its release, ''Red Dead Redemption'' has received a large number of awards. It won several [[Game of the Year]] awards from media outlets such as [[GameSpy]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespy.com/articles/114/1141516p9.html |title=GameSpy Game of the Year 2010 |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |date= |accessdate=June 19, 2012}}</ref> [[GameSpot]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/best-of-2010/game-of-the-year/index.html |title=GameSpot Game of the Year 2010 |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=June 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619193120/http://www.gamespot.com/best-of-2010/game-of-the-year/index.html |archivedate=June 19, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Good Game (television series)|Good Game]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/goodgame/stories/s3085973.htm |title=GG Awards 2010 - Game of the Year |author=''[[Good Game (television series)|Good Game]]'' |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Computer and Video Games]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=280101 |title=Feature: The Top 10 Games of 2010 |author=CVG Staff |publisher=[[Computer And Video Games]] |accessdate=December 22, 2010}}</ref> and [[Machinima.com|Machinima]],<ref name=\"idg\">{{cite web |url=http://blog.machinima.com/insidegaming/2010/12/11/machinima-com-announces-2010-inside-gaming-awards-winners |title=Machinima.com announces 2010 Inside Gaming Awards Winners |first=Billy |last=Shibley |publisher=[[Machinima.com]] |accessdate=December 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714014432/http://blog.machinima.com/insidegaming/2010/12/11/machinima-com-announces-2010-inside-gaming-awards-winners/ |archivedate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> among others.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cnettv.cnet.com/best-video-games-2010/9742-1_53-50097336.html |title=Best Video Games of 2010 |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gamesradar.com/f/the-platinum-chalice-awards-2010/a-2010121616912603042/p-6 |title=The Platinum Chalice Awards 2010 |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=December 20, 2010}}</ref> The game's music also received awards for its original score from GameSpot,<ref name=\"BOM\"/> Machinima.com,<ref name=\"idg\" /> and [[Spike TV]].<ref name=\"spike vgas\"/> [[Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez (singer)|Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez]] also received an award from Spike for his original song \"Far Away\".<ref name=\"spike vgas\"/> The graphics received honors at the Korean Games Conference,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://us.aving.net/news/view.php?articleId=168909&mn_name=news |first=Sophia |last=Kwag |title=KGC AWARDS, to go forward a step with the Global Game Awarding Ceremony |publisher=AVING USA |date=September 20, 2010 |accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> and from the television program ''Good Game''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/goodgame/stories/s3085952.htm |title=GG Awards 2010 - Best Graphics |author=''[[Good Game (television series)|Good Game]]'' |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=December 24, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Red Dead Redemption: Undead Nightmare]]'' also received Best Downloadable content awards from Spike TV,<ref name=\"spike vgas\"/> G4 TV<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.g4tv.com/videos/50341/best-of-2010-best-dlc/ |title=Best of 2010: Best DLC |publisher=[[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4TV]] |date=December 14, 2010 |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref> and [[Game Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/manifesto/2010-gr-awards-best-dlc-3547 |title=Game Revolution: 2010 GR Awards&nbsp;\u2014 Best DLC Add-on |first=Eduardo |last=Reboucas |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=December 24, 2010}}</ref> At the [[Spike Video Game Awards|2010 Spike Video Game Awards]], ''Red Dead Redemption'' won the Game of the Year, Best Song in a Game (\"Far Away\" by [[Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez (singer)|Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez]]), Best Original Score and Best DLC (''[[Red Dead Redemption: Undead Nightmare|Undead Nightmare]]'') awards.<ref name=\"spike vgas\">{{cite web |author=VGA |url=http://www.spike.com/articles/ka13nu/video-game-awards-video-game-awards-2010-winners |title=Video Game Awards 2010 Winners |publisher=[[Spike (TV channel)|Spike]] |date=October 27, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2013}}</ref> ''Red Dead Redemption'' was not nominated for any of the jury based awards at the [[British Academy Video Games Awards|BAFTA Video Game Awards]] due to Rockstar's refusal to submit the title for consideration; BAFTA cannot enter games without permission from the developers and publishers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-03-16-bafta-explains-red-dead-redemption-snub |title=BAFTA explains Red Dead snub |last=Minkley |first=Johnny |website=[[Eurogamer]] |date=March 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.edge-online.com/news/no-red-dead-redemption-baftas/ |title=No Red Dead Redemption at BAFTAs |last=Brown |first=Nathan |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |date=December 15, 2010 |accessdate=May 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!List of awards and nominations for ''Red Dead Redemption''\n|-\n|style=\"padding:0; border:none;\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border:none; margin:0; width:100%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Awards\n!Category\n!Outcome\n!Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"46\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|2010\n|rowspan=\"16\"|[[GameSpot]] Best of 2010\n|Best Story\n|{{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=2 |title=Best Story - The Best Games of 2010 |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=April 9, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011130734/http://gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=2 |archivedate=October 11, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|Best New Character {{small|([[List of Red Dead Redemption characters#John Marston|John Marston]])}}\n|{{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=5 |title=Best New Character - The Best Games of 2010 |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=April 9, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107071026/http://gamespot.com/best-of-2010/special-achievement/index.html?page=5 |archivedate=January 7, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|Best A