{"title_page": "Playmates (song)", "text_new": "{{about|This article is about a famous children's song|the vocal group|The Playmates}}\n\"'''Playmates'''\" is a [[popular music|popular]] [[song]] ostensibly written by [[Saxie Dowell]]. The main theme was note-for-note plagiarized from the 1904 intermezzo \"Iola\" by [[Charles L. Johnson]], for which Johnson sued, settling out of court for an undisclosed sum.\n\nRecordings in [[1940 in music|1940]] were made by [[Kay Kyser]] and his orchestra (vocals: [[Sully Mason]] & His Playmates), by [[Mitchell Ayres]] and His Fashions In Music (vocals: [[Mary Ann Mercer (singer)|Mary Ann Mercer]] & [[Tommy Taylor (musician)|Tommy Taylor]]), and by [[Hal Kemp]] and The Smoothies.  The Johnny McGee orchestra also recorded it in February 1940 with the vocal done by Harry Garret (actually Harry Garey) and Carol Anderson.  Harry's name was misspelled on the Varsity label.\n\nThe [[Kay Kyser]] recording was released by [[Columbia Records]] as catalog number 35375. The record first reached the [[Billboard magazine]] charts on July 20, 1940  (the first week that Billboard listed a chart) and lasted 1 week on the chart, at #4. <ref>\n{{cite book\n  | last = Whitburn\n  | first = Joel\n  | authorlink = Joel Whitburn\n  | title = Top Pop Records 1940-1955\n  | publisher = Record Research\n  | year = 1973 }}\n</ref>\n\nThe song was revived in a [[1953 in music|1953]] recording by [[Jimmy Boyd]], and then again in a [[1955 in music|1955]] recording by [[The Fontane Sisters]]. The recording was released by [[Dot Records]] as catalog number 15370. The song was on the [[Cash Box magazine]] chart for 3 weeks, peaking at #37.\n\n[[Pearls Before Swine (band)|Pearls Before Swine]] included a version on their 1967 debut album \"One Nation Underground\".\n\nA rendition is played in a [[Wee Sing]] video: ''Grandpa's Magical Toys'' (1988).  The music box also plays it over the credits.\n\nA performance by [[the Kipper Kids]] features in the film \"[[The Addams Family (1991 film)|The Addams Family]]\" (1991). A cover by the [[Puppini Sisters]] was also featured in the 2008 comedy-drama film ''[[Kit Kittredge: An American Girl]]''.\n\nKatie Herzig has also covered this song, however, titles it \"Forevermore\". This version was featured in an Australian Target commercial in 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Fontane Sisters}}\n\n[[Category:1940 songs]]\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Saxie Dowell]]\n[[Category:1955 singles]]\n[[Category:The Fontane Sisters songs]]\n[[Category:Pears Before Swine (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Dot Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n\n{{pop-standard-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about||the vocal group|The Playmates}}\n\"'''Playmates'''\" is a [[popular music|popular]] [[song]] ostensibly written by [[Saxie Dowell]]. The main theme was note-for-note plagiarized from the 1904 intermezzo \"Iola\" by [[Charles L. Johnson]], for which Johnson sued, settling out of court for an undisclosed sum.\n\nRecordings in [[1940 in music|1940]] were made by [[Kay Kyser]] and his orchestra (vocals: [[Sully Mason]] & His Playmates), by [[Mitchell Ayres]] and His Fashions In Music (vocals: [[Mary Ann Mercer (singer)|Mary Ann Mercer]] & [[Tommy Taylor (musician)|Tommy Taylor]]), and by [[Hal Kemp]] and The Smoothies.  The Johnny McGee orchestra also recorded it in February 1940 with the vocal done by Harry Garret (actually Harry Garey) and Carol Anderson.  Harry's name was misspelled on the Varsity label.\n\nThe [[Kay Kyser]] recording was released by [[Columbia Records]] as catalog number 35375. The record first reached the [[Billboard magazine]] charts on July 20, 1940  (the first week that Billboard listed a chart) and lasted 1 week on the chart, at #4. <ref>\n{{cite book\n  | last = Whitburn\n  | first = Joel\n  | authorlink = Joel Whitburn\n  | title = Top Pop Records 1940-1955\n  | publisher = Record Research\n  | year = 1973 }}\n</ref>\n\nThe song was revived in a [[1953 in music|1953]] recording by [[Jimmy Boyd]], and then again in a [[1955 in music|1955]] recording by [[The Fontane Sisters]]. The recording was released by [[Dot Records]] as catalog number 15370. The song was on the [[Cash Box magazine]] chart for 3 weeks, peaking at #37.\n\n[[Pearls Before Swine (band)|Pearls Before Swine]] included a version on their 1967 debut album \"One Nation Underground\".\n\nA rendition is played in a [[Wee Sing]] video: ''Grandpa's Magical Toys'' (1988).  The music box also plays it over the credits.\n\nA performance by [[the Kipper Kids]] features in the film \"[[The Addams Family (1991 film)|The Addams Family]]\" (1991). A cover by the [[Puppini Sisters]] was also featured in the 2008 comedy-drama film ''[[Kit Kittredge: An American Girl]]''.\n\nKatie Herzig has also covered this song, however, titles it \"Forevermore\". This version was featured in an Australian Target commercial in 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Fontane Sisters}}\n\n[[Category:1940 songs]]\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Saxie Dowell]]\n[[Category:1955 singles]]\n[[Category:The Fontane Sisters songs]]\n[[Category:Pears Before Swine (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Dot Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n\n{{pop-standard-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BuddyBoy600", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Playmates_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Red Circle Authors", "text_new": "'''Red Circle Authors''' is a British, London-based, publishing house that specialises in [[Japanese fiction]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nihondistractions.blogspot.com/2019/01/stand-in-companion-by-kazufumi-shiraishi.html|title=Japanese Writers' House, Red Circle Team Up|last=|first=|date=30 June 2017|work=AuthorLink: Writers & Readers Magazine|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2018/12/22/books/red-circle-authors-sending-japanese-literature-westward/|title=Red Circle Authors: Sending Japanese literature westward|last=Kosaka|first=Kris|date=22 December 2018|work=The Japan Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://publishingperspectives.com/2019/02/richard-charkin-nine-lessons-from-an-indie-publisher/|title=Nine Lessons From a Small Indie Publisher|last=Charkin|first=Richard|date=13 February 2019|work=Publishing Perspectives|access-date=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nRed Circle Authors was set up in 2016, by Richard Nathan and Koji Chikatani, to showcase Japan\u2019s best creative writing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20190220-00000051-kyodonews-cul|title=\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u66f8\u304d\u4e0b\u308d\u3057\u5c0f\u8aac\u3001\u82f1\u3067\u51fa\u7248\u3000\u73fe\u4ee3\u6587\u5b66\u3092\u4e16\u754c\u306b\u7d39\u4ecb|last=|first=|date=20 February 2019|work=Yahoo News Japan|access-date=20 April 2019}}</ref> The [[Gutai group]] was the initial inspiration behind Red Circle Authors.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2018/12/22/books/red-circle-authors-sending-japanese-literature-westward/|title=Red Circle Authors: Sending Japanese literature westward|date=2018-12-22|website=The Japan Times|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref>\n\nThe Red Circle Authors group currently consists of:\n\n[[Kazufumi Shiraishi]], {{ill|Randy Taguchi|ja|\u7530\u53e3\u30e9\u30f3\u30c7\u30a3}}, [[Fuminori Nakamura]], {{ill|Kanji Hanawa|ja|\u82b1\u8f2a\u839e\u723e}}, [[Mitsuyo Kakuta]], [[Takuji Ichikawa|Takuji Ichikawa,]] [[Soji Shimada]] and [[Roger Pulvers]].\n\nCurrently, only a limited number of literary works by Red Circle's authors are available outside Japan in translation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Life-Arts/Arts/Bull-market-in-bungaku-highlights-Japanese-literary-revival|title=Bull market in bungaku highlights Japanese literary revival|last=Tasker|first=Peter|website=Nikkei Asian Review|date=January 28, 2019|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> Despite this, many of Red Circle's authors have won literary awards in Japan including, for example, the [[Naoki Prize]] ([[Mitsuyo Kakuta]] 2005, [[Kazufumi Shiraishi]] in 2010) and the [[Akutagawa Prize]] ([[Fuminori Nakamura]] in 2005); and have had their works adapted for film and television in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.booksfromjapan.jp/authors/item/787-mitsuyo-kakuta|title=Profile of Mitsuyo Kakuta \u89d2\u7530\u5149\u4ee3 listing film & television adaptations|publisher=Foundation for the Advancement of Juvenile Education in Japan|website=booksfromjapan.jp|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/announcements/just-only-love-the-fifth-mitsuyo-kakuta-book-to-film-adaptation-out-on-general-release/|title=\u2018Just Only Love\u2019 the fifth Mitsuyo Kakuta book-to-film adaptation out on general release|last=Nathan|first=Richard|date=19 April 2019|website=Red Circle Authors|archive-url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/announcements/just-only-love-the-fifth-mitsuyo-kakuta-book-to-film-adaptation-out-on-general-release/|archive-date=20 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=20 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome of the group's authors already have well-established reputations in Asia (in China, Taiwan, Korea, and Thailand, for example)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/announcements/kazufumi-shiraishis-rising-international-profile/|title=Kazufumi Shiraishi\u2019s rising international profile|date=22 November 2017|website=Red Circle Authors}}</ref> and are starting to win international literary prizes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.booksfromjapan.jp/authors/item/420-fuminori-nakamura|title=Profile of Fuminori Nakamura|website=booksfromjapan.jp|publisher=Foundation for the Advancement of Juvenile Education in Japan|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> Fuminori Nakamura<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304692804577281450108634474|title=In Brief: Mysteries|last=|first=|date=17 March 2012|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=}}</ref>, for instance, won the [[David Goodis|David L. Goodis]] Award in 2014.\n\n== Imprint and series ==\nRed Circle Authors' publishing [[Imprint (trade name)|imprint]] is Red Circle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://this.kiji.is/470751663449932897|title=\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u66f8\u304d\u4e0b\u308d\u3057\u5c0f\u8aac\u3001\u82f1\u3067\u51fa\u7248|last=|first=|date=20 February 2019|work=Kyodo News (In Japanese)|access-date=20 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Hazelton|first=Claire|url=https://www.the-tls.co.uk/articles/japan-red-circle-minis-hazelton/|title=Locked in or out? Claire Kohda Hazelton reviews the new Japanese-in-translation imprint Red Circle Minis|date=10 April 2020|work=The Times Literary Supplement (TLS)|access-date=09 April 2020|url-status=live|publisher=The Times Literary Supplement Limited}}</ref>\n\nRed Circle Authors launched this imprint and publishing programme on 23 November 2018 with the launch of its first series Red Circle Minis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/our-publishing-programme/|title=Red Circle's Publishing Programme|publisher=Red Circle Authors|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> and the publication of its first three Minis:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Life-Arts/Arts/Bull-market-in-bungaku-highlights-Japanese-literary-revival|title=Bull market in bungaku highlights Japanese literary revival|last=Tasker|first=Peter|date=28 January 2019|work=Nikkei Asia Review|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n''Stand-In Companion'' by Kazufumi Shiraishi<ref>{{Cite book|title=Stand-In Companion|last=Shiraishi|first=Kazufumi|publisher=Red Circle Authors|year=2018|isbn=1912864002|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/01/26/books/book-reviews/androids-infertility-ethics-collide-kazufumi-shiraishis-dystopian-stand-companion/|title=Androids, infertility and ethics collide in Kazufumi Shiraishi's dystopian 'Stand-in Companion'|last=Gattig|first=Nicolas|date=26 January 2019|work=The Japan Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.complete-review.com/reviews/japannew/shiraishik3.htm|title=Review of Stand-In Companion|date=27 November 2018|website=The Complete Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://literaturkritik.de/id/25560|title=Das philosophische Paradigma in der zeitgen\u00f6ssischen japanischen Literatur|last=Gebhardt|first=Lisette|date=4 April 2019|website=Literatur Kritik|archive-url=https://literaturkritik.de/id/25560|archive-date=20 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=20 April 2019}}</ref>, ''Backlight'' by Kanji Hanawa<ref>{{Cite book|title=Backlight|last=Hanawa|first=Kanji|publisher=Red Circle Authors|year=2018|isbn=1912864045|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.complete-review.com/reviews/japannew/hanawak.htm|title=Review Backlight|date=27 November 2018|website=The Complete Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/06/22/books/book-reviews/backlight-alone-wilds-hokkaido/|title='Backlight': All alone in the wilds of Hokkaido|last=Maloney|first=Iain|date=22 June 2019|work=The Japan Times|access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref> and ''Tokyo Performance'' by Roger Pulvers<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tokyo Performance|last=Pulvers|first=Roger|publisher=Red Circle Authors|year=2018|isbn=1912864029|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://booksonasia.net/book/tokyo-performance/|publisher=Books on Asia|title=Review of Tokyo Performance by Roger Pulvers|website=booksonasia.net|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommentators and reviewers said after their publications that the approach taken was \"not about resizing big books into small objects, but rather about celebrating textual brevity in book form itself\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.popmatters.com/books-red-circle-minis-2630072908.html|title=Small Books for Big Brains: Red Circle Minis' Pocket-sized Japanese Fiction|last=Rollmann|first=Hans|date=15 March 2019|work=PopMatters|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://booksandbao.com/2019/04/16/review-red-circle-minis-three-new-japanese-stories/|title=The Red Circle Minis Collection \u2013 Three New Japanese Stories|last=Harris|first=Will|date=17 April 2019|website=Books And Bao}}</ref> a longtime tradition in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/news-and-views/short-story-writing-in-japan-from-nobel-prize-winners-to-ai/|title=Short Story Writing in Japan: From Nobel Prize winners to AI|last=Nathan|first=Richard|date=16 March 2019|website=The Circle|archive-url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/news-and-views/short-story-writing-in-japan-from-nobel-prize-winners-to-ai/|archive-date=17 March 2019|url-status=|access-date=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nRed Circle Authors' activities are managed from London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20190117/dde/014/070/014000c|title=\u4eba\u6a21\u69d8\uff1a\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u5c0f\u8aac\u3001\u6d77\u5916\u306b\u767a\u4fe1 \u30ea\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30c9\u30fb\u30cd\u30fc\u30b5\u30f3\u3055\u3093\u3001\u8fd1\u8c37\u6d69\u4e8c\u3055\u3093|website=\u6bce\u65e5\u65b0\u805e|language=Japanese}}</ref> The group also has an office in Tokyo. It promotes its select curated group of contemporary Japanese and Japan-based authors and their creative works to the international publishing industry and readers from these two locations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jwh.trannet.co.jp/news/view/78/Red_Circle_Authors_Limited|title=Business Partnership|date=30 June 2017|website=Japanese Writers' House}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jwh.trannet.co.jp/news/view/86/It\u2019s_official__The_Red_Circle_Factbook_is_now_an_\u2018Encyclopedia\u2019|title=It's official: The Red Circle Factbook is now an Encyclopaedia|date=30 March 2018|website=Japanese Writers' House}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to its book publishing Red Circle publishes a magazine on its website, ''The Circle'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/our-magazine/|title=The Circle, Red Circle's magazine, designed for everyone interested Japanese literature, culture and publishing|website=Red Circle Authors|publisher=Red Circle Authors|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> which provides news, analysis and opinion on Japanese literature, writers, publishing, bookselling and culture.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.redcircleauthors.com/ Official website]\n*[https://www.redcircleauthors.com/our-magazine// The Circle]\n*[https://www.redcircleauthors.com/factbook/// Red Circle Factbook]\n[[Category:Book publishing companies based in London]]\n[[Category:Book publishing companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language media]]\n[[Category:Japanese fiction]]\n[[Category:Literary translation]]\n", "text_old": "'''Red Circle Authors''' is a British, London-based, publishing house that specialises in [[Japanese fiction]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nihondistractions.blogspot.com/2019/01/stand-in-companion-by-kazufumi-shiraishi.html|title=Japanese Writers' House, Red Circle Team Up|last=|first=|date=30 June 2017|work=AuthorLink: Writers & Readers Magazine|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2018/12/22/books/red-circle-authors-sending-japanese-literature-westward/|title=Red Circle Authors: Sending Japanese literature westward|last=Kosaka|first=Kris|date=22 December 2018|work=The Japan Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://publishingperspectives.com/2019/02/richard-charkin-nine-lessons-from-an-indie-publisher/|title=Nine Lessons From a Small Indie Publisher|last=Charkin|first=Richard|date=13 February 2019|work=Publishing Perspectives|access-date=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nRed Circle Authors was set up in 2016, by Richard Nathan and Koji Chikatani, to showcase Japan\u2019s best creative writing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20190220-00000051-kyodonews-cul|title=\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u66f8\u304d\u4e0b\u308d\u3057\u5c0f\u8aac\u3001\u82f1\u3067\u51fa\u7248\u3000\u73fe\u4ee3\u6587\u5b66\u3092\u4e16\u754c\u306b\u7d39\u4ecb|last=|first=|date=20 February 2019|work=Yahoo News Japan|access-date=20 April 2019}}</ref> The [[Gutai group]] was the initial inspiration behind Red Circle Authors.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2018/12/22/books/red-circle-authors-sending-japanese-literature-westward/|title=Red Circle Authors: Sending Japanese literature westward|date=2018-12-22|website=The Japan Times|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref>\n\nThe Red Circle Authors group currently consists of:\n\n[[Kazufumi Shiraishi]], {{ill|Randy Taguchi|ja|\u7530\u53e3\u30e9\u30f3\u30c7\u30a3}}, [[Fuminori Nakamura]], {{ill|Kanji Hanawa|ja|\u82b1\u8f2a\u839e\u723e}}, [[Mitsuyo Kakuta]], [[Takuji Ichikawa|Takuji Ichikawa,]] [[Soji Shimada]] and [[Roger Pulvers]].\n\nCurrently, only a limited number of literary works by Red Circle's authors are available outside Japan in translation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Life-Arts/Arts/Bull-market-in-bungaku-highlights-Japanese-literary-revival|title=Bull market in bungaku highlights Japanese literary revival|last=Tasker|first=Peter|website=Nikkei Asian Review|date=January 28, 2019|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> Despite this, many of Red Circle's authors have won literary awards in Japan including, for example, the [[Naoki Prize]] ([[Mitsuyo Kakuta]] 2005, [[Kazufumi Shiraishi]] in 2010) and the [[Akutagawa Prize]] ([[Fuminori Nakamura]] in 2005); and have had their works adapted for film and television in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.booksfromjapan.jp/authors/item/787-mitsuyo-kakuta|title=Profile of Mitsuyo Kakuta \u89d2\u7530\u5149\u4ee3 listing film & television adaptations|publisher=Foundation for the Advancement of Juvenile Education in Japan|website=booksfromjapan.jp|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/announcements/just-only-love-the-fifth-mitsuyo-kakuta-book-to-film-adaptation-out-on-general-release/|title=\u2018Just Only Love\u2019 the fifth Mitsuyo Kakuta book-to-film adaptation out on general release|last=Nathan|first=Richard|date=19 April 2019|website=Red Circle Authors|archive-url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/announcements/just-only-love-the-fifth-mitsuyo-kakuta-book-to-film-adaptation-out-on-general-release/|archive-date=20 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=20 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome of the group's authors already have well-established reputations in Asia (in China, Taiwan, Korea, and Thailand, for example)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/announcements/kazufumi-shiraishis-rising-international-profile/|title=Kazufumi Shiraishi\u2019s rising international profile|date=22 November 2017|website=Red Circle Authors}}</ref> and are starting to win international literary prizes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.booksfromjapan.jp/authors/item/420-fuminori-nakamura|title=Profile of Fuminori Nakamura|website=booksfromjapan.jp|publisher=Foundation for the Advancement of Juvenile Education in Japan|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> Fuminori Nakamura<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304692804577281450108634474|title=In Brief: Mysteries|last=|first=|date=17 March 2012|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=}}</ref>, for instance, won the [[David Goodis|David L. Goodis]] Award in 2014.\n\n== Imprint and series ==\nRed Circle Authors' publishing [[Imprint (trade name)|imprint]] is Red Circle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://this.kiji.is/470751663449932897|title=\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u66f8\u304d\u4e0b\u308d\u3057\u5c0f\u8aac\u3001\u82f1\u3067\u51fa\u7248|last=|first=|date=20 February 2019|work=Kyodo News (In Japanese)|access-date=20 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nRed Circle Authors launched this imprint and publishing programme on 23 November 2018 with the launch of its first series Red Circle Minis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/our-publishing-programme/|title=Red Circle's Publishing Programme|publisher=Red Circle Authors|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> and the publication of its first three Minis:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Life-Arts/Arts/Bull-market-in-bungaku-highlights-Japanese-literary-revival|title=Bull market in bungaku highlights Japanese literary revival|last=Tasker|first=Peter|date=28 January 2019|work=Nikkei Asia Review|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n''Stand-In Companion'' by Kazufumi Shiraishi<ref>{{Cite book|title=Stand-In Companion|last=Shiraishi|first=Kazufumi|publisher=Red Circle Authors|year=2018|isbn=1912864002|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/01/26/books/book-reviews/androids-infertility-ethics-collide-kazufumi-shiraishis-dystopian-stand-companion/|title=Androids, infertility and ethics collide in Kazufumi Shiraishi's dystopian 'Stand-in Companion'|last=Gattig|first=Nicolas|date=26 January 2019|work=The Japan Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.complete-review.com/reviews/japannew/shiraishik3.htm|title=Review of Stand-In Companion|date=27 November 2018|website=The Complete Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://literaturkritik.de/id/25560|title=Das philosophische Paradigma in der zeitgen\u00f6ssischen japanischen Literatur|last=Gebhardt|first=Lisette|date=4 April 2019|website=Literatur Kritik|archive-url=https://literaturkritik.de/id/25560|archive-date=20 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=20 April 2019}}</ref>, ''Backlight'' by Kanji Hanawa<ref>{{Cite book|title=Backlight|last=Hanawa|first=Kanji|publisher=Red Circle Authors|year=2018|isbn=1912864045|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.complete-review.com/reviews/japannew/hanawak.htm|title=Review Backlight|date=27 November 2018|website=The Complete Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/06/22/books/book-reviews/backlight-alone-wilds-hokkaido/|title='Backlight': All alone in the wilds of Hokkaido|last=Maloney|first=Iain|date=22 June 2019|work=The Japan Times|access-date=23 September 2019}}</ref> and ''Tokyo Performance'' by Roger Pulvers<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tokyo Performance|last=Pulvers|first=Roger|publisher=Red Circle Authors|year=2018|isbn=1912864029|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://booksonasia.net/book/tokyo-performance/|publisher=Books on Asia|title=Review of Tokyo Performance by Roger Pulvers|website=booksonasia.net|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommentators and reviewers said after their publications that the approach taken was \"not about resizing big books into small objects, but rather about celebrating textual brevity in book form itself\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.popmatters.com/books-red-circle-minis-2630072908.html|title=Small Books for Big Brains: Red Circle Minis' Pocket-sized Japanese Fiction|last=Rollmann|first=Hans|date=15 March 2019|work=PopMatters|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://booksandbao.com/2019/04/16/review-red-circle-minis-three-new-japanese-stories/|title=The Red Circle Minis Collection \u2013 Three New Japanese Stories|last=Harris|first=Will|date=17 April 2019|website=Books And Bao}}</ref> a longtime tradition in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/news-and-views/short-story-writing-in-japan-from-nobel-prize-winners-to-ai/|title=Short Story Writing in Japan: From Nobel Prize winners to AI|last=Nathan|first=Richard|date=16 March 2019|website=The Circle|archive-url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/news-and-views/short-story-writing-in-japan-from-nobel-prize-winners-to-ai/|archive-date=17 March 2019|url-status=|access-date=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nRed Circle Authors' activities are managed from London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20190117/dde/014/070/014000c|title=\u4eba\u6a21\u69d8\uff1a\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u5c0f\u8aac\u3001\u6d77\u5916\u306b\u767a\u4fe1 \u30ea\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30c9\u30fb\u30cd\u30fc\u30b5\u30f3\u3055\u3093\u3001\u8fd1\u8c37\u6d69\u4e8c\u3055\u3093|website=\u6bce\u65e5\u65b0\u805e|language=Japanese}}</ref> The group also has an office in Tokyo. It promotes its select curated group of contemporary Japanese and Japan-based authors and their creative works to the international publishing industry and readers from these two locations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jwh.trannet.co.jp/news/view/78/Red_Circle_Authors_Limited|title=Business Partnership|date=30 June 2017|website=Japanese Writers' House}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jwh.trannet.co.jp/news/view/86/It\u2019s_official__The_Red_Circle_Factbook_is_now_an_\u2018Encyclopedia\u2019|title=It's official: The Red Circle Factbook is now an Encyclopaedia|date=30 March 2018|website=Japanese Writers' House}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to its book publishing Red Circle publishes a magazine on its website, ''The Circle'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redcircleauthors.com/our-magazine/|title=The Circle, Red Circle's magazine, designed for everyone interested Japanese literature, culture and publishing|website=Red Circle Authors|publisher=Red Circle Authors|access-date=February 3, 2019}}</ref> which provides news, analysis and opinion on Japanese literature, writers, publishing, bookselling and culture.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.redcircleauthors.com/ Official website]\n*[https://www.redcircleauthors.com/our-magazine// The Circle]\n*[https://www.redcircleauthors.com/factbook/// Red Circle Factbook]\n[[Category:Book publishing companies based in London]]\n[[Category:Book publishing companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language media]]\n[[Category:Japanese fiction]]\n[[Category:Literary translation]]\n", "name_user": "WikiGeoffrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImprint and series:Added in new external source to verify this statement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Circle_Authors"}
{"title_page": "Anukul Roy", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian cricketer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Anukul Roy\n|               image = \n|             country = India\n|            fullname =  Anukul Sudhakar Roy\n|          birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|11|30|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Rosera]], [[Jharkhand]]\n|          death_date = \n|         death_place = \n|             batting = Left-handed\n|             bowling = [[Slow left-arm orthodox]]\n|                role = All-rounder \n\n|               club1 = [[Mumbai Indians]] Jharkhand\n|               year1 = 2018-present\n|         clubnumber1 = \n|               club2 = \n|               year2 = \n|         clubnumber2 =\n\n|                date = 3 February 2017\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/player/1079839.html\n}}\n'''Anukul Sudhakar Roy''' (born 30 November 1998) is an [[India]]n [[cricket]]er who plays for [[Jharkhand cricket team|Jharkhand]] and [[Mumbai Indians]]. In December 2017, he was named in India's squad for the [[2018 Under-19 Cricket World Cup]].<ref name=\"IndiaU19\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21650381/prithvi-shaw-lead-india-19-world-cup |title=Prithvi Shaw to lead India in Under-19 World Cup |accessdate=3 December 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> He was the joint highest wicket taker in the Under-19 Cricket World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=11980&type=tournament|title=ICC Under-19 World Cup, 2017/18 Cricket Team Records & Stats - ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in Bhirha, a village near [[Rosera]] in the state of [[Bihar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/u-19-cricket-world-cup-anukul-roy-the-really-cool-star-from-cricket-starved-bihar/story-3EnxCoHn5l4AbBMdZkPR7O.html|title=U-19 cricket World Cup: Anukul Roy, the really cool star from cricket-starved Bihar|date=2018-02-02|website=Hindustantimes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref> He is nicknamed \"[[Samastipur]]'s [[Ravindra Jadeja]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22163953/anukul-roy-samastipur-ravindra-jadeja|title=Anukul Roy, Samastipur's Ravindra Jadeja|date=20 January 2018|website=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[List A cricket|List A]] debut for [[Jharkhand cricket team|Jharkhand]] in the [[2017\u201318 Vijay Hazare Trophy]] on 8 February 2018.<ref name=\"LA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1118740.html |title=Group D, Vijay Hazare Trophy at Secunderabad, Feb 8 2018 |accessdate=8 February 2018 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> He made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut for Jharkhand in the [[2018\u201319 Ranji Trophy]] on 1 November 2018.<ref name=\"FC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1156949.html |title=Elite, Group C, Ranji Trophy at Ranchi, Nov 1-4 2018 |accessdate=1 November 2018 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> He was the leading wicket-taker for Jharkhand in the tournament, with 30 dismissals in nine matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12592;team=6558;type=tournament |title=Ranji Trophy, 2018/19 - Jharkhand: Batting and bowling averages |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> He made his [[Twenty20]] debut for Jharkhand in the [[2018\u201319 Syed Mushtaq Ali Trophy]] on 21 February 2019.<ref name=\"T20\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1157091.html |title=Group A, Syed Mushtaq Ali Trophy at Krishna, Feb 21 2019 |accessdate=21 February 2019 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> In October 2019, he was named in [[India B cricket team|India B]]'s squad for the [[2019\u201320 Deodhar Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/deodhar-trophy-2019-squads-india-a-india-b-india-c-parthiv-patel-shubman-gill-anuma-vihari-ranchi/article29788595.ece |title=Deodhar Trophy 2019: Hanuma Vihari, Parthiv, Shubman to lead; Yashasvi earns call-up |work=SportStar |accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roy, Anukul}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:living people]]\n[[Category:Indian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Jharkhand cricketers]]\n\n{{India-cricket-bio-1998-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian cricketer}}\nKumaresh\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Kumaresh\n|               image = \n|             country = India\n|            fullname =  Kumaresh\n|          birth_date = {{birth date and age|2007|12|29|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Samastipur]], [[Bihar]]\n|          death_date = \n|         death_place = \n|             batting = Left-handed\n|             bowling = [[Slow left-arm orthodox]]\n|                role = All-rounder \n\n|               club1 = [[Mumbai Indians]] Bihar\n|               year1 = 2018-present\n|         clubnumber1 = \n|               club2 = \n|               year2 = \n|         clubnumber2 =\n\n|                date = \n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/player/1079839.html\n}}\n'''Kumaresh''' (born 29 December 2007) is an [[India]]n [[cricket]]er who plays for [[Jharkhand cricket team|Bihar]] and [[Mumbai Indians]]. In December 2017, he was named in India's squad for the [[2018 Under-19 Cricket World Cup]].<ref name=\"IndiaU19\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21650381/prithvi-shaw-lead-india-19-world-cup |title=Prithvi Shaw to lead India in Under-19 World Cup |accessdate=3 December 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> He was the joint highest wicket taker in the Under-19 Cricket World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=11980&type=tournament|title=ICC Under-19 World Cup, 2017/18 Cricket Team Records & Stats - ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in Surajpur, a village near [[Rosera|Samastipur]] in the state of [[Bihar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/u-19-cricket-world-cup-anukul-roy-the-really-cool-star-from-cricket-starved-bihar/story-3EnxCoHn5l4AbBMdZkPR7O.html|title=U-19 cricket World Cup: Anukul Roy, the really cool star from cricket-starved Bihar|date=2018-02-02|website=Hindustantimes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref> He is nicknamed \"[[Samastipur]]'s [[Ravindra Jadeja]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22163953/anukul-roy-samastipur-ravindra-jadeja|title=Anukul Roy, Samastipur's Ravindra Jadeja|date=20 January 2018|website=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[List A cricket|List A]] debut for [[Jharkhand cricket team|Bihar]] in the [[2017\u201318 Vijay Hazare Trophy]] on 8 February 2018.<ref name=\"LA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1118740.html |title=Group D, Vijay Hazare Trophy at Secunderabad, Feb 8 2018 |accessdate=8 February 2018 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> He made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut for Jharkhand in the [[2018\u201319 Ranji Trophy]] on 1 November 2018.<ref name=\"FC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1156949.html |title=Elite, Group C, Ranji Trophy at Ranchi, Nov 1-4 2018 |accessdate=1 November 2018 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> He was the leading wicket-taker for Bihar in the tournament, with 30 dismissals in nine matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12592;team=6558;type=tournament |title=Ranji Trophy, 2018/19 - Jharkhand: Batting and bowling averages |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> He made his [[Twenty20]] debut for Bihar in the [[2018\u201319 Syed Mushtaq Ali Trophy]] on 21 February 2019.<ref name=\"T20\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1157091.html |title=Group A, Syed Mushtaq Ali Trophy at Krishna, Feb 21 2019 |accessdate=21 February 2019 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> In October 2019, he was named in [[India B cricket team|India B]]'s squad for the [[2019\u201320 Deodhar Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/deodhar-trophy-2019-squads-india-a-india-b-india-c-parthiv-patel-shubman-gill-anuma-vihari-ranchi/article29788595.ece |title=Deodhar Trophy 2019: Hanuma Vihari, Parthiv, Shubman to lead; Yashasvi earns call-up |work=SportStar |accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roy, Anukul}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:living people]]\n[[Category:Indian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Jharkhand cricketers]]\n\n{{India-cricket-bio-1998-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "restore to last unvandalised version; hijacking of article with unrelated subject", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anukul_Roy"}
{"title_page": "NBA playoffs", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| current_season = \n| last_season = \n| upcoming_season = 2020 NBA playoffs\n| logo = NBA Playoffs logo (2018).svg\n| pixels =\n| sport = Basketball\n| founded = 1946\n| teams = 16\n| champion = [[Toronto Raptors]]\n| most_champs = [[Boston Celtics]] (17)\n| TV = [[NBA on TNT|TNT]]<br />[[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]]/[[NBA on ABC|ABC]]<br />[[NBA TV]]\n| website = [http://www.nba.com National Basketball Association]\n}}\nThe '''NBA playoffs''' are a [[Best-of-seven playoff|best-of-seven]] [[Knock-out tournament|elimination tournament]] annually held after the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA)\u2019s regular season to determine the league's [[NBA Finals|champion]].\n\n==Format==\n\nIn September 2015, the NBA announced changes to the format of the NBA playoffs that would begin with the [[2016 NBA playoffs]]. The top eight teams in each conference ([[Eastern Conference (NBA)|East]] and [[Western Conference (NBA)|West]]), ranked in order by win-loss records, qualify for the playoffs. The tie-break criteria for playoff seeding and home-court advantage have also changed; head-to-head results between the tied teams is the first tie-breaker, and whether a team won its division championship is the second tie-breaker.<ref name=\"NBA20150908\">{{cite press release|title=NBA to seed conference playoff teams by record|url=http://www.nba.com/2015/news/09/08/nba-to-seed-conference-playoff-teams-by-record/index.html|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth conferences conduct the playoffs in the traditional bracket format. All rounds are [[Best-of-seven playoff|best-of-seven]] series. Series are played in the 2\u20132\u20131\u20131\u20131 format, meaning the team with home-court advantage hosts games 1, 2, 5, and 7, while their opponent hosts games 3, 4, and 6, with games 5\u20137 being played if needed. This format has been used since [[2013\u201314 NBA season|2014]], after NBA team owners unanimously voted to change the format of the NBA finals from the 2\u20133\u20132 format on October 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2013/news/10/23/nba-board-of-governors-format-change.ap/ |title=NBA owners change Finals format to 2-2-1-1-1 |publisher=NBA.com |date=2013-10-23 |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>\n\nThe most common criticism of the current structure is related to parity of conferences. On numerous occasions, [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] teams with losing records qualified for the playoffs, while [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] teams with winning records ended up missing them, including the [[2011 NBA playoffs|2011]], [[2013 NBA playoffs|2013]] and the [[2015 NBA playoffs]]. Weaker Eastern Conference teams also often make it farther in the playoffs due to the conference imbalance.\n\n==History==\nThe National Basketball Association was established in 1949 by merger of the [[Basketball Association of America]] (BAA) and [[National Basketball League (United States)|National Basketball League]] but it recognizes the three BAA seasons as part of its own history. In all of its three years the BAA champion was finally determined in a best-of-seven series but its first two tournaments, the [[1947 BAA Playoffs|1947]] and [[1948 BAA Playoffs]], were otherwise quite different from the third, which 21st-century NBA playoffs nearly match. In 1947 and 1948, the Eastern and Western Division champions were matched in a [[Best-of-seven playoff|best-of-seven]] series following the regular season, whose winner advanced to the championship round. Meanwhile, four runners-up played best-of-three series to determine the other finalist: the two second-place teams were matched in one short series and the two third-place teams in another; the winners of those two series played another one. In 1947 the [[Philadelphia Warriors]] won the runners-up bracket and beat the Western champion [[Chicago Stags]] four games to one, which the NBA recognizes as its first championship; in 1948 Baltimore won the runners-up and beat Eastern champion Philadelphia in the final. Both tournaments generated one finalist from the Eastern and one from the Western Division, but only by chance.<ref name=BBR>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/BAA_1947.html \"1946\u201347 BAA Season Summary\"]. <br>&nbsp; [https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/BAA_1948.html \"1947\u201348 BAA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01. <br>&nbsp; Select \"Next Season\" from the heading for 1947\u201348, and so on. Select \"Finals\" from League Playoffs for the daily schedule of the final series, and so on.</ref>\n\nIn 1949 the third and last BAA tournament matched Eastern teams exclusively and Western teams exclusively, necessarily generating Eastern and Western playoff champions to meet in the final. At the same time, the number of playoff teams was increased from three to four from each Division; two rounds of best-of-three series were played, followed by a best-of-seven championship. The main idea was retained by the NBA. Even the [[1950 NBA Playoffs|1950 tournament]], following a transitional season with three divisions rather than two, initially determined one playoff champion from each division. The Central champion [[Minneapolis Lakers]] became the first league champion under the NBA name by defeating Anderson from the West in a best-of-three, with Syracuse from the East idle, and then knocking off the [[Syracuse Nationals]] in six games.<ref name=BBR2>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/BAA_1949.html \"1948\u201349 BAA Season Summary\"]. <br>&nbsp; [https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1950.html \"1949\u201350 NBA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01.</ref>\n\nThe 1951 through 1953 playoffs changed the division finals into a [[best-of-five playoff]]. With only nine league members in 1953\u201354, the NBA cut its postseason tournament field from eight teams to six (from 1954 through 1966, the period of eight to nine league members). [[Round-robin tournament|Round robins]] were played in 1954, uniquely in NBA history\u2014a three-team round robin among the three playoff teams in each division. From 1955 to 1966, the first-place team in each division was idle while its two runners-up faced played a best-of-three. Division finals were expanded to best-of-seven in 1958 and division semifinals to best-of-five in 1961.\n\nWith ten league members again for the 1966\u201367 season, eight teams were again admitted to the tournament, providing a simple three-round knockout (8-team bracket). A year later, the division semifinals were changed to best-of-seven playoff.  Then, in 1975 and 1977, respectively, a fifth and sixth team were added to each Division, necessitating an additional first round of best-of-three series.\n\nFinally in 1984, the tournament expanded to its present 16-team, four-round knockout, and the now-complete set of first-round series were expanded to a best-of-five. In 2003 the first round was changed to also be best-of-seven.\n\nBeginning with the 2004 season, with the addition of the thirtieth NBA franchise, the [[Charlotte Bobcats]], the NBA realigned its divisions. The result was that each conference would have three divisions of five teams each, and the winner of each division was guaranteed a top-three playoff seed. This would change slightly after the 2005\u201306 season; while division winners still receive automatic playoff berths, they are guaranteed a top-''four'' seed, as described below.\n\n===2006 NBA playoffs controversy===\nThe previous playoff format, in place for the 2004\u201305 and 2005\u201306 NBA playoffs, after the NBA was re-aligned into six divisions, created controversy during the 2005\u201306 season and playoffs and would be changed prior to the 2006\u201307 NBA season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2537369 |title=ESPN \u2013 NBA announces postseason seeding format change \u2013 NBA |publisher=[[ESPN.com]] |date=2006-08-02 |accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2005, NBA division champions were seeded higher than the other teams in their conference, regardless of their record. Prior to 2004, when the NBA was aligned into two conferences with two divisions each, the division champions were guaranteed the top two seeds. This meant that top two teams in a conference (by record) would be seeded either first and second (if they were in opposite divisions) or first and third (if they were in the same division). Because of the NBA playoffs' preset matchups in the second round, this meant that the top two teams in a conference could never meet until the conference finals, assuming they both made it to that round.\n\nAfter the NBA realigned its two conferences into three divisions each, the seeding rules remained largely unchanged. The top three seeds would now be reserved for division champions. However, this meant that if the top two teams (by record) in a conference were in the same division, they would be seeded first and fourth. Assuming no first-round upsets, this raised the prospect that the top two teams in the conference would face each other in the conference semifinals, instead of the conference finals.\n\nIn the second year of this format, the 2005\u201306 NBA season, the two teams with the best records in the Western Conference, the [[San Antonio Spurs]] and [[Dallas Mavericks]] of the [[Southwest Division (NBA)|Southwest Division]], did just that. The Mavericks had the second-best record in the Western Conference and the third-best record in the entire league, behind the [[Detroit Pistons]] and San Antonio. However, they were seeded fourth because they finished second in the Southwest behind the Spurs. This turn of events led to the playoff format being criticized by many. Besides the prospect of a team losing earlier in the playoffs than its regular-season record or seeding would suggest, critics claimed that it also created an unfair advantage for teams in the 2-7/3-6 half of the Western Conference playoff bracket, who could advance to the conference finals without playing either of the two best teams in the conference in an earlier round.\n\nThe [[Phoenix Suns]], winners of the [[Pacific Division (NBA)|Pacific Division]] and possessors of the third best record, were seeded second, while the [[Denver Nuggets]], winners of the [[Northwest Division (NBA)|Northwest Division]] and tied for only the seventh-best record in the conference, were seeded third.\n\nThe [[Memphis Grizzlies]] and [[Los Angeles Clippers]] met in the second-to-last game of the regular season, after the top four seeds had been clinched. The two teams were already determined to be the fifth and sixth seeds, respectively, and had only to determine which rank higher. The fifth seed would likely need to defeat the best two teams in the conference without home-court advantage to advance to the conference finals, as it would face fourth-seeded Dallas in the first round and likely face first-seeded San Antonio if it managed to defeat Dallas. The sixth seed would play third-seeded Denver in the first round, but would have home-court advantage (since the Grizzlies had the fourth-best record in the conference and the Clippers had the fifth-best), and would not have to face either San Antonio or Dallas until the conference finals at the earliest.\n\nThis led to speculation about whether the Grizzlies or the Clippers would have much commitment to winning their match-up in the second-to-last game of the season, since it was clearly most advantageous to lose the game in order to obtain the 6th seed. The Clippers eventually lost to Memphis without much evidence to support the speculation that the Clippers had lost intentionally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=260418029 |title=No losers here? Grizzlies win, Clippers get home court |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=2006-04-19 |accessdate=2015-12-08}}</ref> In the first round of the playoffs, the Clippers defeated the Nuggets in five games, while Memphis was swept by Dallas. Ultimately, Dallas and San Antonio did meet in the second round, with Dallas winning in seven games and advancing all the way to the NBA finals.\n\n===Timeline===\n* [[1947 NBA Playoffs|1947]]: The playoffs were instituted with a three-stage tournament, similar to the [[Stanley Cup playoffs]] of the 1930s; the two first-place teams qualified directly to one semifinal where they played each other in a best-of-7 series.  Teams finishing second & third qualified for the best-of-3 quarterfinals, where the two second-placed teams were paired in one quarterfinal, as were the two third-placed teams, and the two quarterfinal winners played each other in a best-of-three semifinal.  The two semifinal winners played each other in the Basketball Association of America (BAA) best-of-7 final series.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Quarterfinals<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2= Semifinals<br>Best-of-3 (one series)\nBest-of-7 (one series)\n| RD3= BAA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD1-seed1=E3\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=W3\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=W2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E2\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD2-seed1=E3\n| RD2-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score1=\n| RD2-seed2=E2\n| RD2-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score2=\n| RD2-seed3=W1\n| RD2-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score3=\n| RD2-seed4=E1\n| RD2-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score4=\n| RD3-seed1=E2\n| RD3-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score1=\n| RD3-seed2=W1\n| RD3-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score2=\n}}\nThere were no [[Bye (sports)|bye]]s, or idle time, for the division champions \u2013 as there would be for higher-seeded playoff teams 1955\u201366 and 1975\u201383. All six 1947 participants played their first tournament games on Wednesday, April 2; in 1948 the two Eastern runners-up (E2, E3 in the figure) were idle for a few days only because there was a three-way Western tie to break. Both winners of the runners-up bracket, Philadelphia in 1947 and Baltimore in 1948, reached the final series having played fewer tournament games than their final opponents, Chicago in 1947 and Philadelphia in 1948, had played in the best-of-7 pairings of division champions. And both winners of the runners-up bracket won the final series. The \"postseason\" actually comprised 11 games played in a span of 21 days for the 1947 Chicago Stags and 13 games in 30 days for 1948 Philadelphia Warriors, the finalists who emerged from the pairing of division champions.<ref name=BBR/>\n\n* [[1949 NBA Playoffs|1949]]: The playoffs were reorganized to match Eastern Division teams exclusively, and Western Division teams exclusively \u2013 in two halves of the bracket, so to speak. Thus the BAA tournament generated a playoff champion in each Division. (So did the NBA in each of three 1950 divisions, and so it has done in each half of the league since then.)<!--evidently under discussion for 2016--> The top four teams from each of the two divisions qualified.  The quarterfinals and semifinals were renamed division semifinals and division finals, respectively, and both rounds were best-of-3. Thus any playoff team might be eliminated in two games, one home game. The best-of-7 final was unchanged.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Division semifinals<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2= Division finals<br>Best-of-3\n| RD3= BAA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Division\n| group2=Western Division\n| RD1-seed1=E1\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=E4\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=E2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed5=W1\n| RD1-team5=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score5=\n| RD1-seed6=W4\n| RD1-team6=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score6=\n| RD1-seed7=W2\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n| RD2-seed1=E1\n| RD2-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score1=\n| RD2-seed2=E2\n| RD2-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score2=\n| RD2-seed3=W1\n| RD2-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score3=\n| RD2-seed4=W2\n| RD2-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score4=\n| RD3-seed1=E1\n| RD3-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score1=\n| RD3-seed2=W2\n| RD3-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score2=\n}}\n* 1950: The BAA was renamed as the National Basketball Association (NBA).  With a three-division setup, 12 teams now qualified for the playoffs, with the top four teams from each division meeting in the best-of-3 division semifinals.  The winners met in the best-of-3 division finals.  With three teams remaining, the surviving team with the best regular season record qualified directly for the finals while the other two teams met in a best-of-3 NBA semifinals.\n* [[1951 NBA Playoffs|1951]]: With the NBA reverting to a two-division setup; the division semifinals reverted to its original 1949 format with only eight teams qualifying.  The division finals was extended to a best-of-5 format.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Division semifinals<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2= Division finals<br>Best-of-5\n| RD3= NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Division\n| group2=Western Division\n| RD1-seed1=E1\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=E4\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=E2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed5=W1\n| RD1-team5=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score5=\n| RD1-seed6=W4\n| RD1-team6=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score6=\n| RD1-seed7=W2\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n| RD2-seed1=E4\n| RD2-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score1=\n| RD2-seed2=E2\n| RD2-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score2=\n| RD2-seed3=W1\n| RD2-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score3=\n| RD2-seed4=W3\n| RD2-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score4=\n| RD3-seed1=E2\n| RD3-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score1=\n| RD3-seed2=W3\n| RD3-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score2=\n\n}}\n* [[1954 NBA Playoffs|1954]]: With only nine league members (soon to be eight), the number of playoff teams was cut down to six.  The division semifinals was changed to a double [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]] format within the division, with the top three teams from each division qualifying (each team played four games).  Following the round-robin games, the top two teams qualified for the best-of-three division finals, followed by the best-of-seven finals.\n* [[1955 NBA Playoffs|1955]]: The number of playoff teams remained at six, but the initial round-robin was dropped after one year in favor of giving the first-place team in each division a bye to the best-of-five division finals. Teams which placed second and third played a best-of-three division semifinal. In 1955 the byes provided five and six extra days idle for the first-place teams.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1955.html \"1954-55 NBA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01.</ref>\n* [[1958 NBA Playoffs|1958]]: The division finals was extended to a best-of-seven format.\n* [[1961 NBA Playoffs|1961]]: The division semifinals were extended to a best-of-five format.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Division semifinals<br>Best-of-3 (1955\u20131960),\nBest-of-5 (1961\u20131966)\n| RD2= Division finals<br>Best-of-5 (1955\u20131957),\nBest-of-7 (1958\u20131966)\n| RD3= NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Division\n| group2=Western Division\n| RD1-seed3=E2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed7=W2\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n| RD2-seed1=E1\n| RD2-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score1=\n| RD2-seed2=E3\n| RD2-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score2=\n| RD2-seed3=W1\n| RD2-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score3=\n| RD2-seed4=W2\n| RD2-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score4=\n| RD3-seed1=E3\n| RD3-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score1=\n| RD3-seed2=W1\n| RD3-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score2=\n}}\nThe 1961 to 1966 tournaments alone combined initial byes for seeded teams with best-of-five initial series for unseeded teams. The 1961 byes provided five and seven extra days idle for the first-place teams. By 1966 the schedule provided more rest for the first-round participants with byes of 11 and eight extra days idle.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1961.html \"1960-61 NBA Season Summary\"]. <br>&nbsp; [https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1966.html \"1966-66 NBA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01.</ref>\n\n* [[1967 NBA Playoffs|1967]]: The number of playoff teams was expanded to eight once more.  The division semifinals now included the fourth-best team in each conference.  The first-placed teams no longer received a bye.  They were matched against the fourth-placed teams in the best-of-5 division semifinals.\n* [[1968 NBA Playoffs|1968]]: The division semifinals was extended to a best-of-seven format.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Division semifinals<br>Best-of-5 (1967),\nBest-of-7 (1968\u20131970)\n| RD2= Division finals<br>Best-of-7 (1968\u20131970)\n| RD3= NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Division\n| group2=Western Division\n| RD1-seed1=E1\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=E4\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=E2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed5=W1\n| RD1-team5=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score5=\n| RD1-seed6=W4\n| RD1-team6=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score6=\n| RD1-seed7=W2\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n}}\n* [[1970 NBA Playoffs|1970]]: With an increased number of teams, the divisions were upgraded into conferences, which were then split into two divisions.  Eight teams still qualified, four from each conference.  The two division winners were guaranteed at least a #2 seed, and the two best non-division winners from each conference qualified as third and fourth seeds.  Hence, the division semifinals and division finals came to be known as conference semifinals and conference finals, respectively.\n\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD2= Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3= NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed1=E1*\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=E4\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=E2*\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed5=W1*\n| RD1-team5=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score5=\n| RD1-seed6=W4\n| RD1-team6=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score6=\n| RD1-seed7=W2*\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n}}\n* [[1975 NBA Playoffs|1975]]: The number of playoff teams was expanded from eight to ten.  A first round was introduced which matched the fourth and fifth seeds in each conference in a best-of-3 first round series, while the top three seeds received a bye. This is similar to the system currently used in the [[Major League Baseball postseason|MLB]].\n{{4RoundBracket-Byes |RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-team03=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score03=\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-team04=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score04=\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-team11=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score11=\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-team12=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score12=\n| RD2-seed01=E1*\n| RD2-team01=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score01=\n| RD2-seed02=\n| RD2-team02=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score02=\n| RD2-seed03=E2*\n| RD2-team03=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score03=\n| RD2-seed04=E3\n| RD2-team04=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score04=\n| RD2-seed05=W1*\n| RD2-team05=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score05=\n| RD2-seed06=\n| RD2-team06=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score06=\n| RD2-seed07=W2*\n| RD2-team07=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score07=\n| RD2-seed08=W3\n| RD2-team08=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score08=\n}}\n*[[1977 NBA Playoffs|1977]]: The number of playoff teams was expanded from 10 to 12.  The first round now included the sixth best team in each conference, which was matched against the third seed.  Only the division winners received byes to the next round. This is similar to the format currently used by the [[NFL playoffs|NFL]].\n{{4RoundBracket-Byes |RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-team03=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score03=\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-team04=\n| RD1-score04=\n| RD1-seed05=E3\n| RD1-team05=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score05=\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-team06=\n| RD1-score06=\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-team11=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score11=\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-team12=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score12=\n| RD1-seed13=W3\n| RD1-team13=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score13=\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-team14=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score14=\n| RD2-seed01=E1*\n| RD2-team01=\n| RD2-score01=\n| RD2-seed02=\n| RD2-team02=\n| RD2-score02=\n| RD2-seed03=E2*\n| RD2-team03=\n| RD2-score03=\n| RD2-seed04=\n| RD2-team04=\n| RD2-score04=\n| RD2-seed05=W1*\n| RD2-team05=\n| RD2-score05=\n| RD2-seed06=\n| RD2-team06=\n| RD2-score06=\n| RD2-seed07=W2*\n| RD2-team07=\n| RD2-score07=\n| RD2-seed08=\n| RD2-team08=\n| RD2-score08=\n}}\nThe 1983 tournament is the latest to incorporate first-round byes for seeded teams. The first-round best-of-three series tapped off on Tuesday and Wednesday, April 19 and 20; the second-round best-of-sevens on Sunday to the following Wednesday, April 27. Counting from Tuesday the byes provided five to eight extra days idle.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1983.html \"1982\u201383 NBA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01.</ref>\n\n* [[1984 NBA Playoffs|1984]]: The playoffs were expanded from 12 teams to 16 teams.  All teams now participated in the first round, which was extended to a best-of-five series.\n{{16TeamBracket | RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-5\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed01=E1*\n| RD1-seed02=E8\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-seed05=E3\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-seed07=E2*\n| RD1-seed08=E7\n| RD1-seed09=W1*\n| RD1-seed10=W8\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-seed13=W3\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-seed15=W2*\n| RD1-seed16=W7\n}}\n* [[2003 NBA Playoffs|2003]]: The first round was extended to a best-of-seven series. This change arguably benefitted the higher seeds as it reduced the likelihood of an upset by a lower seed. It also meant that a team that swept their series 4\u20130 might have to wait up to two weeks to play their next series against a team that had won 4\u20133.\n{{16TeamBracket | RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-7\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed01=E1*\n| RD1-seed02=E8\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-seed05=E3\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-seed07=E2*\n| RD1-seed08=E7\n| RD1-seed09=W1*\n| RD1-seed10=W8\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-seed13=W3\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-seed15=W2*\n| RD1-seed16=W7\n}}\n* [[2005 NBA Playoffs|2005]]: Each conference was realigned into three divisions with each division winner qualifying for a top-three seed regardless of record.  The next best five teams from each conference also qualify for the playoffs.\n{{16TeamBracket | RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-7\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed01=E1*\n| RD1-seed02=E8\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-seed05=E3*\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-seed07=E2*\n| RD1-seed08=E7\n| RD1-seed09=W1*\n| RD1-seed10=W8\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-seed13=W3*\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-seed15=W2*\n| RD1-seed16=W7\n}}\n* [[2007 NBA Playoffs|2007]]: To address the criticisms of having each division champion guaranteed a top-three seed, regardless of record, the rules were changed such that the division winners are now only guaranteed a top-four seed.  The team with the second-best record in the conference is now guaranteed the second seed, even if it finishes second in its own division.  This ensures that the two best teams in the conference will not meet until the conference finals at the earliest.  The previous system raised the prospect of the two best teams in the conference being seeded 1 and 4 if they play in the same division, thus forcing them to play each other in the second round (given no upsets).\n** Note: In the example below, the East's #2 seed is not a division champion.\n{{16TeamBracket | RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-7\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed01=E1*\n| RD1-seed02=E8\n| RD1-seed03=E5\n| RD1-seed04=E4*\n| RD1-seed05=E3*\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-seed07=E2\n| RD1-seed08=E7\n| RD1-seed09=W1*\n| RD1-seed10=W8\n| RD1-seed11=W5\n| RD1-seed12=W4\n| RD1-seed13=W3*\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-seed15=W2*\n| RD1-seed16=W7\n}}\n\n* [[2016 NBA Playoffs|2016]]: While the playoff bracketing did not change, qualification criteria were changed. The teams with the eight best records in each conference receive playoff berths, with no automatic berths nor guaranteed top-four seed placement for division champions.\n\n==Team roster==\nPlayoff teams must identify their postseason roster before the playoffs begin. They are allowed up to 15 players and can designate two as inactive for each game.<ref name=pastuszek>{{cite news|last=Pastuszek|first=Jon|title=Pastuszek: Could Yi Jianlian Help an NBA Playoff Team?|date=April 9, 2013|work=SheridanHoops.com|url=http://www.sheridanhoops.com/2013/04/09/pastuszek-could-yi-jianlian-help-an-nba-playoff-team/|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref> Players are eligible to be on a team's playoff roster as long as they were on the team for at least one regular season game, and were not on another NBA team's roster after March 1.<ref>{{cite news|last=Helin|first=Kurt|title=Winderman: Still time to add good player (or Eddy Curry) to playoff roster|date=March 21, 2011|work=NBCSports.com|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/03/21/winderman-still-time-to-add-good-player-or-eddy-curry-to-playoff-roster/|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref> Previously{{when|date=April 2018}}, playoff rosters were limited to 12 players who were named before the playoffs began.<ref name=pastuszek/>\n\n==Records and statistics==\n* Only five 8th seeded teams have managed to win a series versus the number 1 seeded team:  The [[Denver Nuggets]] eliminated the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] 3\u20132 in 1994. The [[New York Knicks]] eliminated the [[Miami Heat]] 3\u20132 in 1999. The [[Golden State Warriors]] defeated the [[Dallas Mavericks]] 4\u20132 in the 2007 Western Conference First Round (becoming the first 8 seed to beat a 1 seed in the best of 7 format). In 2011, the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] beat the [[San Antonio Spurs]], 4\u20132 and in 2012, the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] beat the [[Chicago Bulls]]  4\u20132.\n* The 1999 Knicks are the only 8th seeded team ever to reach the [[1999 NBA Finals|NBA finals]]; no 8th seeded team has won the NBA finals as of 2019.\n* The 1956\u201357 [[St. Louis Hawks]], 1958\u201359 [[Minneapolis Lakers]] and the 1980\u201381 [[Houston Rockets]] are the only teams with losing records (34-38, 33\u201339 and 40\u201342, respectively) to make it to the NBA finals. In 1981, the Houston Rockets' opponent in the Western Conference Finals, the [[Kansas City Kings]], also had a losing record (40\u201342). [[Boston Celtics]] beat all of these teams in the finals.\n* The [[1994\u201395 Houston Rockets season|1994\u201395 Houston Rockets]], a sixth seed with a record of 47\u201335, are the lowest seeded team to win the NBA finals. In the NBA finals, the Rockets swept the [[Orlando Magic]] (57\u201325) in four games; in doing so, the Rockets defeated four teams that had won 50 or more games during the regular season (the [[Utah Jazz]] at 60\u201322, the [[Phoenix Suns]] at 59\u201323, the [[San Antonio Spurs]] at 62\u201320 and Orlando at 57\u201325), the first time a team had done so. As of now, the 1994-1995 Rockets are the only team to have won an NBA title without having the home-court advantage during any round of the playoffs.\n* The Golden State Warriors own the longest NBA playoff winning streak for a single postseason with 15 straight wins in the 2017 playoffs.  \n* Of all the teams with multiple NBA finals appearances, the [[Chicago Bulls]] are the only team to have never lost in the finals, winning six.\n* The [[Boston Celtics]] possess the most overall NBA finals series wins with an overall record of 17\u20134. The [[Los Angeles Lakers|Los Angeles/Minneapolis Lakers]] have played in the most NBA finals series (31), with an overall record of 16\u201315.\n* The longest active playoff appearance streak currently belongs to the San Antonio Spurs with 22 consecutive appearances in the playoffs, beginning in the 1997\u201398 NBA season. The longest ever streak of playoffs appearances in a row is currently shared between the Spurs and the [[Philadelphia 76ers|Syracuse Nationals/Philadelphia 76ers]], who made the playoffs 22 straight years from the 1949\u201350 season to the 1970\u201371 season.\n*Of the current NBA teams the Sacramento Kings and the Phoenix Suns have the longest playoff droughts currently. The Kings haven't been to the playoffs since 2006 losing in the first round. The Phoenix Suns haven't been back to the playoffs since 2010 after losing in the western conference finals.  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fadeawayworld.net/2019/04/05/12-nba-teams-with-the-longest-current-playoff-droughts/|website=fadeawayworld.net|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* In [[1983 NBA Playoffs|1983]], under the bye-7-7-7 system, the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] attained the best record of 12-1, having only lost in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference Finals against the [[Milwaukee Bucks]].\n* In [[2001 NBA Playoffs|2001]], under the best of 5-7-7-7 system, the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] attained the best record of 15-1, having only lost in Game 1 of the [[2001 NBA Finals|Finals]] against the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].\n* In [[2017 NBA Playoffs|2017]], under the best of 7-7-7-7 system, the [[Golden State Warriors]] attained the best record of 16-1, having only lost in Game 4 of the [[2017 NBA Finals|Finals]] against the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]. The Warriors and Cavaliers came into the Finals with a combined record of 24-1, with the Cavaliers having only lost in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference Finals against the [[Boston Celtics]].\n* Of the 73 [[List of NBA champions|NBA champions]], 71 of them were either a No. 1 seed (49), a No. 2 seed (16) or a No. 3 seed (6).\n*Of the 73 NBA champions, 38 of them were from the eastern conference while the other 33 were from the western conference. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/teams-with-the-most-nba-championships.html|title=Teams With The Most NBA Championships|website=WorldAtlas|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Playoff appearances==\n''Current as of the [[2020 NBA playoffs]]''\n\n===Appearances by active teams===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Team\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Appearances<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.nba.com/history/?ls=iref:nba:gnav |title=Franchise History |publisher=NBA.com |date=February 17, 2015 |accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n|61 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Minneapolis Lakers (1947\u20131960).|group=upper-alpha|name=b}}\n|-\n|[[Boston Celtics]]\n|57\n|-\n|[[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n|49 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Syracuse Nationals (1946\u20131963).|group=upper-alpha|name=c}}\n|-\n|[[Atlanta Hawks]]\n|46 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Tri-Cities Blackhawks (1946\u20131951), the Milwaukee Hawks (1951\u20131955), and the St. Louis Hawks (1955\u20131968).|group=upper-alpha|name=d}}\n|-\n|[[Detroit Pistons]]\n|42 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Fort Wayne Pistons (1949\u20131957).|group=upper-alpha|name=e}}\n|-\n|[[New York Knicks]]\n|41 \n|-\n|[[San Antonio Spurs]]\n|39 {{#tag:ref|Does not include appearances in the [[American Basketball Association]] (ABA) playoffs. Per the conditions of the [[ABA&ndash;NBA merger]], the NBA does not officially recognize the ABA history, playoffs and records.|group=upper-alpha|name=a}}\n|-\n|[[Chicago Bulls]]\n|35\n|-\n|[[Golden State Warriors]]\n|35 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Philadelphia Warriors (1946\u20131962) and the San Francisco Warriors (1962\u20131971).|group=upper-alpha|name=f}}\n|-\n|[[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n|35\n|-\n|[[Houston Rockets]]\n|33 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the San Diego Rockets (1967\u20131971).|group=upper-alpha|name=h}}\n|-\n|[[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n|32\n|-\n|[[Oklahoma City Thunder]]\n|31 {{#tag:ref|As part of the 2008 relocation settlement with the [[Seattle|City of Seattle]], the Thunder officially shares its history with that of the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] (1967\u20132008).<ref>{{cite web|title=Details of settlement between Bennett, Seattle revealed|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3545175|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=May 7, 2015}}</ref>|group=upper-alpha|name=i}}\n|-\n|[[Phoenix Suns]]\n|29\n|-\n|[[Sacramento Kings]]\n|29 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Rochester Royals (1948\u20131957), the Cincinnati Royals (1957\u20131972), the Kansas City-Omaha Kings (1972\u20131975), and the Kansas City Kings (1975\u20131985).|group=upper-alpha|name=g}}\n|-\n|[[Washington Wizards]]\n|29 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Chicago Packers (1961\u20131962), the Chicago Zephyrs (1962\u20131963), the Baltimore Bullets (1963\u20131973), the Capital Bullets (1973\u20131974), and the Washington Bullets (1974\u20131997).|group=upper-alpha|name=j}}\n|-\n|[[Utah Jazz]]\n|28 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the New Orleans Jazz (1974\u20131979).|group=upper-alpha|name=k}}\n|-\n|[[Indiana Pacers]]\n|26 <ref group=upper-alpha name=a />\n|-\n|[[Denver Nuggets]]\n|25 <ref group=upper-alpha name=a />\n|-\n|[[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n|22\n|-\n|[[Dallas Mavericks]]\n|21\n|-\n|[[Brooklyn Nets]]\n|20 <ref group=upper-alpha name=a />{{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the New Jersey Nets (1977\u20132012).|group=upper-alpha|name=l}}\n|-\n|[[Miami Heat]]\n|20\n|-\n|[[Orlando Magic]]\n|15\n|-\n|[[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n|14 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the [[Buffalo Braves]] (1970\u20131978).|group=upper-alpha|name=m}}\n|-\n|[[Toronto Raptors]]\n|12\n|-\n|[[Charlotte Hornets]]\n|10 {{#tag:ref|The New Orleans Pelicans were originally named the Charlotte Hornets, and moved to [[New Orleans]] in {{nbay|2002|start}}. A new team, the Charlotte Bobcats, was then established in {{nbay|2004|start}}. When the Charlotte team reclaimed the Hornets name in a 2014 agreement, the Charlotte team also reclaimed the history of the original Hornets; as such, the New Orleans Pelicans were established in 2002, and the Bobcats/Hornets rejoined the NBA in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charlotte Hornets Name Returns to Carolinas |url=http://www.nba.com/hornets/charlotte-hornets-name-returns-carolinas |publisher=Charlotte Hornets |date=May 20, 2014 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>|group=upper-alpha|name=n}}\n|-\n|[[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n|10 \n|-\n|[[Minnesota Timberwolves]]\n|9\n|-\n|[[New Orleans Pelicans]]\n|7 <ref group=upper-alpha name=n />\n|}\n{{reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[NBA Conference Finals]]\n*[[NBA Finals]]\n*[[NBA D-League Playoffs]]\n*[[NBA D-League Finals]]\n*[[List of NBA playoff series]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nba.com NBA] official website\n* [http://www.nba.com/features/seedingprimer07.html Playoff Seeding Criteria] NBA.com\n* [http://www.insidehoops.com/playoffs.shtml NBA Playoffs] InsideHoops.com coverage\n* [https://www.basketball-reference.com/playoffs/ Basketball-Reference.com] Index of NBA playoffs seasons\n\n{{NBAPlayoffs}}\n{{NBA}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nba Playoffs}}\n[[Category:National Basketball Association playoffs| ]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1947]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| current_season = \n| last_season = \n| upcoming_season = 2020 NBA playoffs\n| logo = NBA Playoffs logo (2018).svg\n| pixels =\n| sport = Basketball\n| founded = 1946\n| teams = 16\n| champion = [[Toronto Raptors]]\n| most_champs = [[Boston Celtics]] (17)\n| TV = [[NBA on TNT|TNT]]<br />[[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]]/[[NBA on ABC|ABC]]<br />[[NBA TV]]\n| website = [http://www.nba.com National Basketball Association]\n}}\nThe '''NBA playoffs''' are a [[Best-of-seven playoff|best-of-seven]] [[Knock-out tournament|elimination tournament]] annually held after the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA)\u2019s regular season to determine the league's [[NBA Finals|champion]].\n\n==Format==\n\nIn September 2015, the NBA announced changes to the format of the NBA playoffs that would begin with the [[2016 NBA playoffs]]. The top eight teams in each conference ([[Eastern Conference (NBA)|East]] and [[Western Conference (NBA)|West]]), ranked in order by win-loss records, qualify for the playoffs. The tie-break criteria for playoff seeding and home-court advantage have also changed; head-to-head results between the tied teams is the first tie-breaker, and whether a team won its division championship is the second tie-breaker.<ref name=\"NBA20150908\">{{cite press release|title=NBA to seed conference playoff teams by record|url=http://www.nba.com/2015/news/09/08/nba-to-seed-conference-playoff-teams-by-record/index.html|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth conferences conduct the playoffs in the traditional bracket format. All rounds are [[Best-of-seven playoff|best-of-seven]] series. Series are played in the 2\u20132\u20131\u20131\u20131 format, meaning the team with home-court advantage hosts games 1, 2, 5, and 7, while their opponent hosts games 3, 4, and 6, with games 5\u20137 being played if needed. This format has been used since [[2013\u201314 NBA season|2014]], after NBA team owners unanimously voted to change the format of the NBA finals from the 2\u20133\u20132 format on October 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2013/news/10/23/nba-board-of-governors-format-change.ap/ |title=NBA owners change Finals format to 2-2-1-1-1 |publisher=NBA.com |date=2013-10-23 |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>\n\nThe most common criticism of the current structure is related to parity of conferences. On numerous occasions, [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] teams with losing records qualified for the playoffs, while [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] teams with winning records ended up missing them, including the [[2011 NBA playoffs|2011]], [[2013 NBA playoffs|2013]] and the [[2015 NBA playoffs]]. Weaker Eastern Conference teams also often make it farther in the playoffs due to the conference imbalance.\n\n==History==\nThe National Basketball Association was established in 1949 by merger of the [[Basketball Association of America]] (BAA) and [[National Basketball League (United States)|National Basketball League]] but it recognizes the three BAA seasons as part of its own history. In all of its three years the BAA champion was finally determined in a best-of-seven series but its first two tournaments, the [[1947 BAA Playoffs|1947]] and [[1948 BAA Playoffs]], were otherwise quite different from the third, which 21st-century NBA playoffs nearly match. In 1947 and 1948, the Eastern and Western Division champions were matched in a [[Best-of-seven playoff|best-of-seven]] series following the regular season, whose winner advanced to the championship round. Meanwhile, four runners-up played best-of-three series to determine the other finalist: the two second-place teams were matched in one short series and the two third-place teams in another; the winners of those two series played another one. In 1947 the [[Philadelphia Warriors]] won the runners-up bracket and beat the Western champion [[Chicago Stags]] four games to one, which the NBA recognizes as its first championship; in 1948 Baltimore won the runners-up and beat Eastern champion Philadelphia in the final. Both tournaments generated one finalist from the Eastern and one from the Western Division, but only by chance.<ref name=BBR>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/BAA_1947.html \"1946\u201347 BAA Season Summary\"]. <br>&nbsp; [https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/BAA_1948.html \"1947\u201348 BAA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01. <br>&nbsp; Select \"Next Season\" from the heading for 1947\u201348, and so on. Select \"Finals\" from League Playoffs for the daily schedule of the final series, and so on.</ref>\n\nIn 1949 the third and last BAA tournament matched Eastern teams exclusively and Western teams exclusively, necessarily generating Eastern and Western playoff champions to meet in the final. At the same time, the number of playoff teams was increased from three to four from each Division; two rounds of best-of-three series were played, followed by a best-of-seven championship. The main idea was retained by the NBA. Even the [[1950 NBA Playoffs|1950 tournament]], following a transitional season with three divisions rather than two, initially determined one playoff champion from each division. The Central champion [[Minneapolis Lakers]] became the first league champion under the NBA name by defeating Anderson from the West in a best-of-three, with Syracuse from the East idle, and then knocking off the [[Syracuse Nationals]] in six games.<ref name=BBR2>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/BAA_1949.html \"1948\u201349 BAA Season Summary\"]. <br>&nbsp; [https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1950.html \"1949\u201350 NBA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01.</ref>\n\nThe 1951 through 1953 playoffs changed the division finals into a [[best-of-five playoff]]. With only nine league members in 1953\u201354, the NBA cut its postseason tournament field from eight teams to six (from 1954 through 1966, the period of eight to nine league members). [[Round-robin tournament|Round robins]] were played in 1954, uniquely in NBA history\u2014a three-team round robin among the three playoff teams in each division. From 1955 to 1966, the first-place team in each division was idle while its two runners-up faced played a best-of-three. Division finals were expanded to best-of-seven in 1958 and division semifinals to best-of-five in 1961.\n\nWith ten league members again for the 1966\u201367 season, eight teams were again admitted to the tournament, providing a simple three-round knockout (8-team bracket). A year later, the division semifinals were changed to best-of-seven playoff.  Then, in 1975 and 1977, respectively, a fifth and sixth team were added to each Division, necessitating an additional first round of best-of-three series.\n\nFinally in 1984, the tournament expanded to its present 16-team, four-round knockout, and the now-complete set of first-round series were expanded to a best-of-five. In 2003 the first round was changed to also be best-of-seven.\n\nBeginning with the 2004 season, with the addition of the thirtieth NBA franchise, the [[Charlotte Bobcats]], the NBA realigned its divisions. The result was that each conference would have three divisions of five teams each, and the winner of each division was guaranteed a top-three playoff seed. This would change slightly after the 2005\u201306 season; while division winners still receive automatic playoff berths, they are guaranteed a top-''four'' seed, as described below.\n\n===2006 NBA playoffs controversy===\nThe previous playoff format, in place for the 2004\u201305 and 2005\u201306 NBA playoffs, after the NBA was re-aligned into six divisions, created controversy during the 2005\u201306 season and playoffs and would be changed prior to the 2006\u201307 NBA season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2537369 |title=ESPN \u2013 NBA announces postseason seeding format change \u2013 NBA |publisher=[[ESPN.com]] |date=2006-08-02 |accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2005, NBA division champions were seeded higher than the other teams in their conference, regardless of their record. Prior to 2004, when the NBA was aligned into two conferences with two divisions each, the division champions were guaranteed the top two seeds. This meant that top two teams in a conference (by record) would be seeded either first and second (if they were in opposite divisions) or first and third (if they were in the same division). Because of the NBA playoffs' preset matchups in the second round, this meant that the top two teams in a conference could never meet until the conference finals, assuming they both made it to that round.\n\nAfter the NBA realigned its two conferences into three divisions each, the seeding rules remained largely unchanged. The top three seeds would now be reserved for division champions. However, this meant that if the top two teams (by record) in a conference were in the same division, they would be seeded first and fourth. Assuming no first-round upsets, this raised the prospect that the top two teams in the conference would face each other in the conference semifinals, instead of the conference finals.\n\nIn the second year of this format, the 2005\u201306 NBA season, the two teams with the best records in the Western Conference, the [[San Antonio Spurs]] and [[Dallas Mavericks]] of the [[Southwest Division (NBA)|Southwest Division]], did just that. The Mavericks had the second-best record in the Western Conference and the third-best record in the entire league, behind the [[Detroit Pistons]] and San Antonio. However, they were seeded fourth because they finished second in the Southwest behind the Spurs. This turn of events led to the playoff format being criticized by many. Besides the prospect of a team losing earlier in the playoffs than its regular-season record or seeding would suggest, critics claimed that it also created an unfair advantage for teams in the 2-7/3-6 half of the Western Conference playoff bracket, who could advance to the conference finals without playing either of the two best teams in the conference in an earlier round.\n\nThe [[Phoenix Suns]], winners of the [[Pacific Division (NBA)|Pacific Division]] and possessors of the third best record, were seeded second, while the [[Denver Nuggets]], winners of the [[Northwest Division (NBA)|Northwest Division]] and tied for only the seventh-best record in the conference, were seeded third.\n\nThe [[Memphis Grizzlies]] and [[Los Angeles Clippers]] met in the second-to-last game of the regular season, after the top four seeds had been clinched. The two teams were already determined to be the fifth and sixth seeds, respectively, and had only to determine which rank higher. The fifth seed would likely need to defeat the best two teams in the conference without home-court advantage to advance to the conference finals, as it would face fourth-seeded Dallas in the first round and likely face first-seeded San Antonio if it managed to defeat Dallas. The sixth seed would play third-seeded Denver in the first round, but would have home-court advantage (since the Grizzlies had the fourth-best record in the conference and the Clippers had the fifth-best), and would not have to face either San Antonio or Dallas until the conference finals at the earliest.\n\nThis led to speculation about whether the Grizzlies or the Clippers would have much commitment to winning their match-up in the second-to-last game of the season, since it was clearly most advantageous to lose the game in order to obtain the 6th seed. The Clippers eventually lost to Memphis without much evidence to support the speculation that the Clippers had lost intentionally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=260418029 |title=No losers here? Grizzlies win, Clippers get home court |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=2006-04-19 |accessdate=2015-12-08}}</ref> In the first round of the playoffs, the Clippers defeated the Nuggets in five games, while Memphis was swept by Dallas. Ultimately, Dallas and San Antonio did meet in the second round, with Dallas winning in seven games and advancing all the way to the NBA finals.\n\n===Timeline===\n* [[1947 NBA Playoffs|1947]]: The playoffs were instituted with a three-stage tournament, similar to the [[Stanley Cup playoffs]] of the 1930s; the two first-place teams qualified directly to one semifinal where they played each other in a best-of-7 series.  Teams finishing second & third qualified for the best-of-3 quarterfinals, where the two second-placed teams were paired in one quarterfinal, as were the two third-placed teams, and the two quarterfinal winners played each other in a best-of-three semifinal.  The two semifinal winners played each other in the Basketball Association of America (BAA) best-of-7 final series.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Quarterfinals<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2= Semifinals<br>Best-of-3 (one series)\nBest-of-7 (one series)\n| RD3= BAA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD1-seed1=E3\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=W3\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=W2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E2\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD2-seed1=E3\n| RD2-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score1=\n| RD2-seed2=E2\n| RD2-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score2=\n| RD2-seed3=W1\n| RD2-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score3=\n| RD2-seed4=E1\n| RD2-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score4=\n| RD3-seed1=E2\n| RD3-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score1=\n| RD3-seed2=W1\n| RD3-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score2=\n}}\nThere were no [[Bye (sports)|bye]]s, or idle time, for the division champions \u2013 as there would be for higher-seeded playoff teams 1955\u201366 and 1975\u201383. All six 1947 participants played their first tournament games on Wednesday, April 2; in 1948 the two Eastern runners-up (E2, E3 in the figure) were idle for a few days only because there was a three-way Western tie to break. Both winners of the runners-up bracket, Philadelphia in 1947 and Baltimore in 1948, reached the final series having played fewer tournament games than their final opponents, Chicago in 1947 and Philadelphia in 1948, had played in the best-of-7 pairings of division champions. And both winners of the runners-up bracket won the final series. The \"postseason\" actually comprised 11 games played in a span of 21 days for the 1947 Chicago Stags and 13 games in 30 days for 1948 Philadelphia Warriors, the finalists who emerged from the pairing of division champions.<ref name=BBR/>\n\n* [[1949 NBA Playoffs|1949]]: The playoffs were reorganized to match Eastern Division teams exclusively, and Western Division teams exclusively \u2013 in two halves of the bracket, so to speak. Thus the BAA tournament generated a playoff champion in each Division. (So did the NBA in each of three 1950 divisions, and so it has done in each half of the league since then.)<!--evidently under discussion for 2016--> The top four teams from each of the two divisions qualified.  The quarterfinals and semifinals were renamed division semifinals and division finals, respectively, and both rounds were best-of-3. Thus any playoff team might be eliminated in two games, one home game. The best-of-7 final was unchanged.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Division semifinals<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2= Division finals<br>Best-of-3\n| RD3= BAA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Division\n| group2=Western Division\n| RD1-seed1=E1\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=E4\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=E2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed5=W1\n| RD1-team5=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score5=\n| RD1-seed6=W4\n| RD1-team6=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score6=\n| RD1-seed7=W2\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n| RD2-seed1=E1\n| RD2-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score1=\n| RD2-seed2=E2\n| RD2-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score2=\n| RD2-seed3=W1\n| RD2-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score3=\n| RD2-seed4=W2\n| RD2-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score4=\n| RD3-seed1=E1\n| RD3-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score1=\n| RD3-seed2=W2\n| RD3-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score2=\n}}\n* 1950: The BAA was renamed as the National Basketball Association (NBA).  With a three-division setup, 12 teams now qualified for the playoffs, with the top four teams from each division meeting in the best-of-3 division semifinals.  The winners met in the best-of-3 division finals.  With three teams remaining, the surviving team with the best regular season record qualified directly for the finals while the other two teams met in a best-of-3 NBA semifinals.\n* [[1951 NBA Playoffs|1951]]: With the NBA reverting to a two-division setup; the division semifinals reverted to its original 1949 format with only eight teams qualifying.  The division finals was extended to a best-of-5 format.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Division semifinals<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2= Division finals<br>Best-of-5\n| RD3= NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Division\n| group2=Western Division\n| RD1-seed1=E1\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=E4\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=E2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed5=W1\n| RD1-team5=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score5=\n| RD1-seed6=W4\n| RD1-team6=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score6=\n| RD1-seed7=W2\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n| RD2-seed1=E4\n| RD2-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score1=\n| RD2-seed2=E2\n| RD2-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score2=\n| RD2-seed3=W1\n| RD2-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score3=\n| RD2-seed4=W3\n| RD2-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score4=\n| RD3-seed1=E2\n| RD3-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score1=\n| RD3-seed2=W3\n| RD3-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score2=\n\n}}\n* [[1954 NBA Playoffs|1954]]: With only nine league members (soon to be eight), the number of playoff teams was cut down to six.  The division semifinals was changed to a double [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]] format within the division, with the top three teams from each division qualifying (each team played four games).  Following the round-robin games, the top two teams qualified for the best-of-three division finals, followed by the best-of-seven finals.\n* [[1955 NBA Playoffs|1955]]: The number of playoff teams remained at six, but the initial round-robin was dropped after one year in favor of giving the first-place team in each division a bye to the best-of-five division finals. Teams which placed second and third played a best-of-three division semifinal. In 1955 the byes provided five and six extra days idle for the first-place teams.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1955.html \"1954-55 NBA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01.</ref>\n* [[1958 NBA Playoffs|1958]]: The division finals was extended to a best-of-seven format.\n* [[1961 NBA Playoffs|1961]]: The division semifinals were extended to a best-of-five format.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Division semifinals<br>Best-of-3 (1955\u20131960),\nBest-of-5 (1961\u20131966)\n| RD2= Division finals<br>Best-of-5 (1955\u20131957),\nBest-of-7 (1958\u20131966)\n| RD3= NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Division\n| group2=Western Division\n| RD1-seed3=E2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed7=W2\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n| RD2-seed1=E1\n| RD2-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score1=\n| RD2-seed2=E3\n| RD2-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score2=\n| RD2-seed3=W1\n| RD2-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score3=\n| RD2-seed4=W2\n| RD2-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score4=\n| RD3-seed1=E3\n| RD3-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score1=\n| RD3-seed2=W1\n| RD3-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD3-score2=\n}}\nThe 1961 to 1966 tournaments alone combined initial byes for seeded teams with best-of-five initial series for unseeded teams. The 1961 byes provided five and seven extra days idle for the first-place teams. By 1966 the schedule provided more rest for the first-round participants with byes of 11 and eight extra days idle.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1961.html \"1960-61 NBA Season Summary\"]. <br>&nbsp; [https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1966.html \"1966-66 NBA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01.</ref>\n\n* [[1967 NBA Playoffs|1967]]: The number of playoff teams was expanded to eight once more.  The division semifinals now included the fourth-best team in each conference.  The first-placed teams no longer received a bye.  They were matched against the fourth-placed teams in the best-of-5 division semifinals.\n* [[1968 NBA Playoffs|1968]]: The division semifinals was extended to a best-of-seven format.\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Division semifinals<br>Best-of-5 (1967),\nBest-of-7 (1968\u20131970)\n| RD2= Division finals<br>Best-of-7 (1968\u20131970)\n| RD3= NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Division\n| group2=Western Division\n| RD1-seed1=E1\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=E4\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=E2\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed5=W1\n| RD1-team5=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score5=\n| RD1-seed6=W4\n| RD1-team6=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score6=\n| RD1-seed7=W2\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n}}\n* [[1970 NBA Playoffs|1970]]: With an increased number of teams, the divisions were upgraded into conferences, which were then split into two divisions.  Eight teams still qualified, four from each conference.  The two division winners were guaranteed at least a #2 seed, and the two best non-division winners from each conference qualified as third and fourth seeds.  Hence, the division semifinals and division finals came to be known as conference semifinals and conference finals, respectively.\n\n{{3RoundBracket-Byes | RD1= Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD2= Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3= NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed1=E1*\n| RD1-team1=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score1=\n| RD1-seed2=E4\n| RD1-team2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score2=\n| RD1-seed3=E2*\n| RD1-team3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score3=\n| RD1-seed4=E3\n| RD1-team4=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score4=\n| RD1-seed5=W1*\n| RD1-team5=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score5=\n| RD1-seed6=W4\n| RD1-team6=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score6=\n| RD1-seed7=W2*\n| RD1-team7=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score7=\n| RD1-seed8=W3\n| RD1-team8=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score8=\n}}\n* [[1975 NBA Playoffs|1975]]: The number of playoff teams was expanded from eight to ten.  A first round was introduced which matched the fourth and fifth seeds in each conference in a best-of-3 first round series, while the top three seeds received a bye. This is similar to the system currently used in the [[Major League Baseball postseason|MLB]].\n{{4RoundBracket-Byes |RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-team03=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score03=\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-team04=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score04=\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-team11=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score11=\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-team12=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score12=\n| RD2-seed01=E1*\n| RD2-team01=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score01=\n| RD2-seed02=\n| RD2-team02=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score02=\n| RD2-seed03=E2*\n| RD2-team03=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score03=\n| RD2-seed04=E3\n| RD2-team04=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score04=\n| RD2-seed05=W1*\n| RD2-team05=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score05=\n| RD2-seed06=\n| RD2-team06=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score06=\n| RD2-seed07=W2*\n| RD2-team07=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score07=\n| RD2-seed08=W3\n| RD2-team08=&nbsp;\n| RD2-score08=\n}}\n*[[1977 NBA Playoffs|1977]]: The number of playoff teams was expanded from 10 to 12.  The first round now included the sixth best team in each conference, which was matched against the third seed.  Only the division winners received byes to the next round. This is similar to the format currently used by the [[NFL playoffs|NFL]].\n{{4RoundBracket-Byes |RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-3\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-team03=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score03=\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-team04=\n| RD1-score04=\n| RD1-seed05=E3\n| RD1-team05=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score05=\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-team06=\n| RD1-score06=\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-team11=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score11=\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-team12=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score12=\n| RD1-seed13=W3\n| RD1-team13=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score13=\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-team14=&nbsp;\n| RD1-score14=\n| RD2-seed01=E1*\n| RD2-team01=\n| RD2-score01=\n| RD2-seed02=\n| RD2-team02=\n| RD2-score02=\n| RD2-seed03=E2*\n| RD2-team03=\n| RD2-score03=\n| RD2-seed04=\n| RD2-team04=\n| RD2-score04=\n| RD2-seed05=W1*\n| RD2-team05=\n| RD2-score05=\n| RD2-seed06=\n| RD2-team06=\n| RD2-score06=\n| RD2-seed07=W2*\n| RD2-team07=\n| RD2-score07=\n| RD2-seed08=\n| RD2-team08=\n| RD2-score08=\n}}\nThe 1983 tournament is the latest to incorporate first-round byes for seeded teams. The first-round best-of-three series tapped off on Tuesday and Wednesday, April 19 and 20; the second-round best-of-sevens on Sunday to the following Wednesday, April 27. Counting from Tuesday the byes provided five to eight extra days idle.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_1983.html \"1982\u201383 NBA Season Summary\"]. Basketball-Reference.com. Retrieved 2015-03-01.</ref>\n\n* [[1984 NBA Playoffs|1984]]: The playoffs were expanded from 12 teams to 16 teams.  All teams now participated in the first round, which was extended to a best-of-five series.\n{{16TeamBracket | RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-5\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed01=E1*\n| RD1-seed02=E8\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-seed05=E3\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-seed07=E2*\n| RD1-seed08=E7\n| RD1-seed09=W1*\n| RD1-seed10=W8\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-seed13=W3\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-seed15=W2*\n| RD1-seed16=W7\n}}\n* [[2003 NBA Playoffs|2003]]: The first round was extended to a best-of-seven series. This change arguably benefitted the higher seeds as it reduced the likelihood of an upset by a lower seed. It also meant that a team that swept their series 4\u20130 might have to wait up to two weeks to play their next series against a team that had won 4\u20133.\n{{16TeamBracket | RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-7\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed01=E1*\n| RD1-seed02=E8\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-seed05=E3\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-seed07=E2*\n| RD1-seed08=E7\n| RD1-seed09=W1*\n| RD1-seed10=W8\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-seed13=W3\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-seed15=W2*\n| RD1-seed16=W7\n}}\n* [[2005 NBA Playoffs|2005]]: Each conference was realigned into three divisions with each division winner qualifying for a top-three seed regardless of record.  The next best five teams from each conference also qualify for the playoffs.\n{{16TeamBracket | RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-7\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed01=E1*\n| RD1-seed02=E8\n| RD1-seed03=E4\n| RD1-seed04=E5\n| RD1-seed05=E3*\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-seed07=E2*\n| RD1-seed08=E7\n| RD1-seed09=W1*\n| RD1-seed10=W8\n| RD1-seed11=W4\n| RD1-seed12=W5\n| RD1-seed13=W3*\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-seed15=W2*\n| RD1-seed16=W7\n}}\n* [[2007 NBA Playoffs|2007]]: To address the criticisms of having each division champion guaranteed a top-three seed, regardless of record, the rules were changed such that the division winners are now only guaranteed a top-four seed.  The team with the second-best record in the conference is now guaranteed the second seed, even if it finishes second in its own division.  This ensures that the two best teams in the conference will not meet until the conference finals at the earliest.  The previous system raised the prospect of the two best teams in the conference being seeded 1 and 4 if they play in the same division, thus forcing them to play each other in the second round (given no upsets).\n** Note: In the example below, the East's #2 seed is not a division champion.\n{{16TeamBracket | RD1=First Round<br>Best-of-7\n| RD2=Conference semifinals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD3=Conference finals<br>Best-of-7\n| RD4=NBA finals<br>Best-of-7\n| group1=Eastern Conference\n| group2=Western Conference\n| RD1-seed01=E1*\n| RD1-seed02=E8\n| RD1-seed03=E5\n| RD1-seed04=E4*\n| RD1-seed05=E3*\n| RD1-seed06=E6\n| RD1-seed07=E2\n| RD1-seed08=E7\n| RD1-seed09=W1*\n| RD1-seed10=W8\n| RD1-seed11=W5\n| RD1-seed12=W4\n| RD1-seed13=W3*\n| RD1-seed14=W6\n| RD1-seed15=W2*\n| RD1-seed16=W7\n}}\n\n* [[2016 NBA Playoffs|2016]]: While the playoff bracketing did not change, qualification criteria were changed. The teams with the eight best records in each conference receive playoff berths, with no automatic berths nor guaranteed top-four seed placement for division champions.\n\n==Team roster==\nPlayoff teams must identify their postseason roster before the playoffs begin. They are allowed up to 15 players and can designate two as inactive for each game.<ref name=pastuszek>{{cite news|last=Pastuszek|first=Jon|title=Pastuszek: Could Yi Jianlian Help an NBA Playoff Team?|date=April 9, 2013|work=SheridanHoops.com|url=http://www.sheridanhoops.com/2013/04/09/pastuszek-could-yi-jianlian-help-an-nba-playoff-team/|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref> Players are eligible to be on a team's playoff roster as long as they were on the team for at least one regular season game, and were not on another NBA team's roster after March 1.<ref>{{cite news|last=Helin|first=Kurt|title=Winderman: Still time to add good player (or Eddy Curry) to playoff roster|date=March 21, 2011|work=NBCSports.com|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/03/21/winderman-still-time-to-add-good-player-or-eddy-curry-to-playoff-roster/|accessdate=April 16, 2013}}</ref> Previously{{when|date=April 2018}}, playoff rosters were limited to 12 players who were named before the playoffs began.<ref name=pastuszek/>\n\n==Records and statistics==\n* Only five 8th seeded teams have managed to win a series versus the number 1 seeded team:  The [[Denver Nuggets]] eliminated the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] 3\u20132 in 1994. The [[New York Knicks]] eliminated the [[Miami Heat]] 3\u20132 in 1999. The [[Golden State Warriors]] defeated the [[Dallas Mavericks]] 4\u20132 in the 2007 Western Conference First Round (becoming the first 8 seed to beat a 1 seed in the best of 7 format). In 2011, the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] beat the [[San Antonio Spurs]], 4\u20132 and in 2012, the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] beat the [[Chicago Bulls]]  4\u20132.\n* The 1999 Knicks are the only 8th seeded team ever to reach the [[1999 NBA Finals|NBA finals]]; no 8th seeded team has won the NBA finals as of 2019.\n* The 1956\u201357 [[St. Louis Hawks]], 1958\u201359 [[Minneapolis Lakers]] and the 1980\u201381 [[Houston Rockets]] are the only teams with losing records (34-38, 33\u201339 and 40\u201342, respectively) to make it to the NBA finals. In 1981, the Houston Rockets' opponent in the Western Conference Finals, the [[Kansas City Kings]], also had a losing record (40\u201342). [[Boston Celtics]] beat all of these teams in the finals.\n* The [[1994\u201395 Houston Rockets season|1994\u201395 Houston Rockets]], a sixth seed with a record of 47\u201335, are the lowest seeded team to win the NBA finals. In the NBA finals, the Rockets swept the [[Orlando Magic]] (57\u201325) in four games; in doing so, the Rockets defeated four teams that had won 50 or more games during the regular season (the [[Utah Jazz]] at 60\u201322, the [[Phoenix Suns]] at 59\u201323, the [[San Antonio Spurs]] at 62\u201320 and Orlando at 57\u201325), the first time a team had done so. As of now, the 1994-1995 Rockets are the only team to have won an NBA title without having the home-court advantage during any round of the playoffs.\n* The Golden State Warriors own the longest NBA playoff winning streak for a single postseason with 15 straight wins in the 2017 playoffs.  \n* Of all the teams with multiple NBA finals appearances, the [[Chicago Bulls]] are the only team to have never lost in the finals, winning six.\n* The [[Boston Celtics]] possess the most overall NBA finals series wins with an overall record of 17\u20134. The [[Los Angeles Lakers|Los Angeles/Minneapolis Lakers]] have played in the most NBA finals series (31), with an overall record of 16\u201315.\n* The longest active playoff appearance streak currently belongs to the San Antonio Spurs with 22 consecutive appearances in the playoffs, beginning in the 1997\u201398 NBA season. The longest ever streak of playoffs appearances in a row is currently shared between the Spurs and the [[Philadelphia 76ers|Syracuse Nationals/Philadelphia 76ers]], who made the playoffs 22 straight years from the 1949\u201350 season to the 1970\u201371 season.\n*Of the current NBA teams the Sacremento Kings and the Phoenix Suns have the longest playoff droughts currently. The Kings haven't been to the playoffs since 2006 losing in the first round. The Phoenix Suns haven't been back to the playoffs since 2010 after losing in the western conference finals.  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fadeawayworld.net/2019/04/05/12-nba-teams-with-the-longest-current-playoff-droughts/|website=fadeawayworld.net|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* In [[1983 NBA Playoffs|1983]], under the bye-7-7-7 system, the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] attained the best record of 12-1, having only lost in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference Finals against the [[Milwaukee Bucks]].\n* In [[2001 NBA Playoffs|2001]], under the best of 5-7-7-7 system, the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] attained the best record of 15-1, having only lost in Game 1 of the [[2001 NBA Finals|Finals]] against the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].\n* In [[2017 NBA Playoffs|2017]], under the best of 7-7-7-7 system, the [[Golden State Warriors]] attained the best record of 16-1, having only lost in Game 4 of the [[2017 NBA Finals|Finals]] against the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]. The Warriors and Cavaliers came into the Finals with a combined record of 24-1, with the Cavaliers having only lost in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference Finals against the [[Boston Celtics]].\n* Of the 73 [[List of NBA champions|NBA champions]], 71 of them were either a No. 1 seed (49), a No. 2 seed (16) or a No. 3 seed (6).\n*Of the 73 NBA champions, 38 of them were from the eastern conference while the other 33 were from the western conference. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/teams-with-the-most-nba-championships.html|title=Teams With The Most NBA Championships|website=WorldAtlas|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Playoff appearances==\n''Current as of the [[2020 NBA playoffs]]''\n\n===Appearances by active teams===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Team\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Appearances<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.nba.com/history/?ls=iref:nba:gnav |title=Franchise History |publisher=NBA.com |date=February 17, 2015 |accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n|61 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Minneapolis Lakers (1947\u20131960).|group=upper-alpha|name=b}}\n|-\n|[[Boston Celtics]]\n|57\n|-\n|[[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n|49 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Syracuse Nationals (1946\u20131963).|group=upper-alpha|name=c}}\n|-\n|[[Atlanta Hawks]]\n|46 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Tri-Cities Blackhawks (1946\u20131951), the Milwaukee Hawks (1951\u20131955), and the St. Louis Hawks (1955\u20131968).|group=upper-alpha|name=d}}\n|-\n|[[Detroit Pistons]]\n|42 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Fort Wayne Pistons (1949\u20131957).|group=upper-alpha|name=e}}\n|-\n|[[New York Knicks]]\n|41 \n|-\n|[[San Antonio Spurs]]\n|39 {{#tag:ref|Does not include appearances in the [[American Basketball Association]] (ABA) playoffs. Per the conditions of the [[ABA&ndash;NBA merger]], the NBA does not officially recognize the ABA history, playoffs and records.|group=upper-alpha|name=a}}\n|-\n|[[Chicago Bulls]]\n|35\n|-\n|[[Golden State Warriors]]\n|35 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Philadelphia Warriors (1946\u20131962) and the San Francisco Warriors (1962\u20131971).|group=upper-alpha|name=f}}\n|-\n|[[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n|35\n|-\n|[[Houston Rockets]]\n|33 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the San Diego Rockets (1967\u20131971).|group=upper-alpha|name=h}}\n|-\n|[[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n|32\n|-\n|[[Oklahoma City Thunder]]\n|31 {{#tag:ref|As part of the 2008 relocation settlement with the [[Seattle|City of Seattle]], the Thunder officially shares its history with that of the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] (1967\u20132008).<ref>{{cite web|title=Details of settlement between Bennett, Seattle revealed|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3545175|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=May 7, 2015}}</ref>|group=upper-alpha|name=i}}\n|-\n|[[Phoenix Suns]]\n|29\n|-\n|[[Sacramento Kings]]\n|29 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Rochester Royals (1948\u20131957), the Cincinnati Royals (1957\u20131972), the Kansas City-Omaha Kings (1972\u20131975), and the Kansas City Kings (1975\u20131985).|group=upper-alpha|name=g}}\n|-\n|[[Washington Wizards]]\n|29 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the Chicago Packers (1961\u20131962), the Chicago Zephyrs (1962\u20131963), the Baltimore Bullets (1963\u20131973), the Capital Bullets (1973\u20131974), and the Washington Bullets (1974\u20131997).|group=upper-alpha|name=j}}\n|-\n|[[Utah Jazz]]\n|28 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the New Orleans Jazz (1974\u20131979).|group=upper-alpha|name=k}}\n|-\n|[[Indiana Pacers]]\n|26 <ref group=upper-alpha name=a />\n|-\n|[[Denver Nuggets]]\n|25 <ref group=upper-alpha name=a />\n|-\n|[[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n|22\n|-\n|[[Dallas Mavericks]]\n|21\n|-\n|[[Brooklyn Nets]]\n|20 <ref group=upper-alpha name=a />{{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the New Jersey Nets (1977\u20132012).|group=upper-alpha|name=l}}\n|-\n|[[Miami Heat]]\n|20\n|-\n|[[Orlando Magic]]\n|15\n|-\n|[[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n|14 {{#tag:ref|Includes appearances as the [[Buffalo Braves]] (1970\u20131978).|group=upper-alpha|name=m}}\n|-\n|[[Toronto Raptors]]\n|12\n|-\n|[[Charlotte Hornets]]\n|10 {{#tag:ref|The New Orleans Pelicans were originally named the Charlotte Hornets, and moved to [[New Orleans]] in {{nbay|2002|start}}. A new team, the Charlotte Bobcats, was then established in {{nbay|2004|start}}. When the Charlotte team reclaimed the Hornets name in a 2014 agreement, the Charlotte team also reclaimed the history of the original Hornets; as such, the New Orleans Pelicans were established in 2002, and the Bobcats/Hornets rejoined the NBA in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charlotte Hornets Name Returns to Carolinas |url=http://www.nba.com/hornets/charlotte-hornets-name-returns-carolinas |publisher=Charlotte Hornets |date=May 20, 2014 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>|group=upper-alpha|name=n}}\n|-\n|[[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n|10 \n|-\n|[[Minnesota Timberwolves]]\n|9\n|-\n|[[New Orleans Pelicans]]\n|7 <ref group=upper-alpha name=n />\n|}\n{{reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[NBA Conference Finals]]\n*[[NBA Finals]]\n*[[NBA D-League Playoffs]]\n*[[NBA D-League Finals]]\n*[[List of NBA playoff series]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nba.com NBA] official website\n* [http://www.nba.com/features/seedingprimer07.html Playoff Seeding Criteria] NBA.com\n* [http://www.insidehoops.com/playoffs.shtml NBA Playoffs] InsideHoops.com coverage\n* [https://www.basketball-reference.com/playoffs/ Basketball-Reference.com] Index of NBA playoffs seasons\n\n{{NBAPlayoffs}}\n{{NBA}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nba Playoffs}}\n[[Category:National Basketball Association playoffs| ]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1947]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NBA_playoffs"}
